aS'Here are The Times\xe2\x80\x99s recommendations in some of Tuesday\xe2\x80\x99s Democratic primary races in New York City. The polls will be open from 6 a.m. to 9 p.m.\n has effectively governed a difficult city, with crime continuing its remarkable decline, municipal finances remaining sound and innovations like universal prekindergarten put in place.\n stands out in a strong field, having ably pursued criminal justice reforms since being suddenly put in charge of an office that can be a model for prosecutorial practices nationwide.\n Our favorite in a talented field, someone who wants to improve the city\xe2\x80\x99s already fine campaign finance law and enhance Council transparency.\n The incumbent, who valorously supported a school desegregation plan for her district in the face of opposition from various interests.\n A young community leader who has focused on transportation issues and affordable housing, and is endorsed by the departing council member, James Vacca.\n An assemblyman who deserves every vote over his thoroughly discredited opponent, a former state senator who went to prison, Hiram Monserrate.\n The incumbent, to continue his efforts to help immigrants under siege by a hostile federal administration, he should be given four more years.\n'
