aS'The voter-fraud crusaders who run President Trump\xe2\x80\x99s electoral-integrity commission have found their holy grail: evidence that large-scale illegal voting swung a pivotal Senate election in 2016. \nIn his latest \n, Kris Kobach, the commission\xe2\x80\x99s vice chairman, called it \xe2\x80\x9chighly likely\xe2\x80\x9d that the election of Maggie Hassan, New Hampshire\xe2\x80\x99s Democratic candidate for the Senate, was \xe2\x80\x9cstolen through voter fraud.\xe2\x80\x9d He said it was \xe2\x80\x9cpossible\xe2\x80\x9d that Hillary Clinton\xe2\x80\x99s narrow victory in the state was the result of illegal voting, too.\nMr. Kobach\xe2\x80\x99s evidence for these explosive claims? \xe2\x80\x9cProof,\xe2\x80\x9d he says, that 5,313 people who voted in New Hampshire in 2016 do not actually reside in the state. The theory, which has been \n, is that these voters sneaked over the border \xe2\x80\x94 or were even bused in! \xe2\x80\x94 from neighboring Democratic strongholds like Massachusetts or Vermont, in a huge conspiracy to swing the election.\nThat scheme had national implications, Mr. Kobach wrote \xe2\x80\x94 the Senate failed to repeal Obamacare by one vote.\nAnd he wonders why serious people don\xe2\x80\x99t take him seriously.\nIn his day job as Kansas\xe2\x80\x99 secretary of state, where he plays the \n Mr. Kobach complains that the media\xe2\x80\x99s response to his efforts to safeguard America\xe2\x80\x99s elections is a dismissive, \xe2\x80\x9cMove along, there\xe2\x80\x99s nothing to see here.\xe2\x80\x9d So let\xe2\x80\x99s stop and take a closer look.\nTrue, New Hampshire \n. Mrs. Clinton won by 2,736 votes, or 0.3 percentage points. Ms. Hassan\xe2\x80\x99s margin was slimmer \xe2\x80\x94 1,017 votes out of nearly three-quarters of a million cast.\nAlso apparently true: Data given to the commission by the speaker of the state\xe2\x80\x99s House showed that 6,540 people registered to vote there on Election Day using an out-of-state ID.\nUnder state law, new residents have 60 days to get a New Hampshire driver\xe2\x80\x99s license. Yet of those 6,540 people, Mr. Kobach said, 5,526 have not done so. Of those, only 213 have registered a vehicle in the state, leaving 5,313 voters who are not, as Mr. Kobach put it, \xe2\x80\x9cbona fide residents of the state.\xe2\x80\x9d\nBusted, right? Not quite. In his hunger to expose fraudulent voters, Mr. Kobach omitted \n. New Hampshire law \n people to be \xe2\x80\x9cresidents\xe2\x80\x9d to register and vote. They must only be \xe2\x80\x9cdomiciled\xe2\x80\x9d in the state, meaning that New Hampshire is where they currently live and spend most of their time \xe2\x80\x94 a description that applies, incidentally, to many college students. In 2016, the towns with the highest rates of voters who registered using out-of-state IDs were \n.\nMr. Kobach didn\xe2\x80\x99t say whether he had attempted to contact any of the supposed scofflaws, but \n. The first four it reached identified themselves as college students who lived in New Hampshire last November.\nVice President Mike Pence, the commission\xe2\x80\x99s chairman, \n that the commission had \xe2\x80\x9cno preconceived notions or preordained results.\xe2\x80\x9d That was never credible. It\xe2\x80\x99s laughable now, as Mr. Kobach spouts his latest, wildly irresponsible accusations based on an inaccurate reading of the data and the law.\nRather than admit his obvious biases, Mr. Kobach \n that \xe2\x80\x9cthe mainstream media has ignored the problem of voter fraud and belittled those of us who are trying to do something about it.\xe2\x80\x9d The truth is that Mr. Kobach and his band of vote suppressors belittle themselves, and threaten voting rights nationwide, with their dishonesty.\nIn a convenient stroke of timing, the commission will hold its \n in New Hampshire on Tuesday. The topic is voter confidence in electoral integrity \xe2\x80\x94 amusing coming from the people who\xe2\x80\x99ve done their utmost to undermine that confidence with baseless allegations.\n'
