aS'Prime Minister Hun Sen of \n has been in power for more than 30 years. On Wednesday, he vowed to stay in power. \xe2\x80\x9cAfter witnessing the treasonous acts of some Cambodians in recent days,\xe2\x80\x9d he said, \xe2\x80\x9cI have decided to continue my job for another 10 years.\xe2\x80\x9d\nCitizens might have thought it was up to them to decide, in general elections next year, who will govern their country. Mr. Hun Sen has set them straight: He has no intention of losing that election or future ones to an opposition that did better than expected in the last \n. If this means charging opposition leaders with treason, so be it.\nEarlier this month, Kem Sokha, leader of the opposition Cambodia National Rescue Party, was \n on absurd charges of plotting to overthrow Mr. Hun Sen\xe2\x80\x99s government. The charges were based on a 2013 video in which Mr. Kem Sokha spoke of bringing democratic change to Cambodia.\nMr. Hun Sen\xe2\x80\x99s government has also forced the 24-year-old \n newspaper to close over trumped-up charges of tax evasion. That comes on the heels of the closing of 15 independent radio stations broadcasting programs from Voice of America and Radio Free Asia. \xe2\x80\x9cAfter they close down all the independent newspapers and radio stations,\xe2\x80\x9d the Daily reporter Aun Pheap observed, \xe2\x80\x9cno one will be able to print true information for the upcoming election.\xe2\x80\x9d\nSenator John McCain has \n the Trump administration, which has shown little concern about the global rise of autocracy, to \xe2\x80\x9csend a strong message that the United States is committed to promoting democracy, human rights and rule of law in Cambodia and throughout the world.\xe2\x80\x9d The \n has asked for Mr. Kem Sokha\xe2\x80\x99s release.\nMr. Hun Sen has much at stake. His family has grown \n in a country ranked the most corrupt in Southeast Asia by \n. He has the support of China, which provided Cambodia with nearly \n in loans and investment from 2011 to 2015.\nBut if he doesn\xe2\x80\x99t drop the charges against Mr. Kem Sokha; permit a credible political opposition; and allow The Daily, radio stations and all news outlets to operate freely, the world will know that Cambodia is no longer a democracy.\n'
