aS'An inscription on the lobby wall greets visitors in Latin at the offices of the New York City medical examiner. It is an adage familiar to places where autopsies are performed. Reasonably translated, it says: \xe2\x80\x9cLet conversation cease. Let laughter flee. This is the place where death rejoices to help the living.\xe2\x80\x9d\nAnother saying, borrowed from the Book of Proverbs, Chapter 31, might also work were it to be put on that wall: \xe2\x80\x9cSpeak up for those who cannot speak for themselves.\xe2\x80\x9d That, too, is what the medical examiner\xe2\x80\x99s office is about. Rarely has it been called upon to speak up as relentlessly as it has for those whose voices were silenced at the World Trade Center 16 years ago.\nFor the chief medical examiner, Dr. Barbara Sampson, and her staff, the terrorist attacks of Sept. 11, 2001, are never past. All these years later, the team still strives to \n each of the 2,753 people who were killed in the destruction of the twin towers. \xe2\x80\x9cWe made a commitment to the families that we would do whatever it takes, for as long as it takes,\xe2\x80\x9d Dr. Sampson said. \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re the family physician to the bereaved.\xe2\x80\x9d\nDeath certificates for the victims were issued long ago. But assigning identities to the 21,905 human remains that were recovered from the wreckage is a separate matter. Only 1,641 of the 2,753 victims \xe2\x80\x94 60 percent \xe2\x80\x94 have been positively identified, mostly through DNA analysis. The success rate is slightly better, 64 percent, in regard to the 405 firefighters, police officers and emergency medical workers who died at ground zero.\nTime has not been a friend of the forensic teams. \n \xe2\x80\x94 a man who, at his family\xe2\x80\x99s request, has not been publicly named \xe2\x80\x94 became known to them a month ago. This was nearly two and a half years after No. 1,640 was identified: \n, a 26-year-old technology specialist who worked on the 97th floor of the south tower. Before that, six months had gone by since No. 1,639: \n, 31, the lone Belgian citizen among the victims. He worked on the 97th floor of the north tower.\n\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s a slow go,\xe2\x80\x9d Dr. Sampson said. \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re now down to the ones that are very difficult to get useful DNA.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThe genetic material that\xe2\x80\x99s available is sometimes no more than the tiniest patch of flesh. Some remains lay in the wreckage for weeks, months, even years \xe2\x80\x94 degraded by water, burning jet fuel and all manner of debris from the downed buildings. In addition, bacterial DNA intermingled with human matter. \xe2\x80\x9cIt was the worst combination of events you could have for a DNA specimen,\xe2\x80\x9d said Dr. Sampson, who has been the city\xe2\x80\x99s chief medical examiner since December 2014.\nRecent scientific advances, including what she described as a bone-extraction technique, made it possible to identify the 1,641st victim. That gives her hope that the process is not stuck. \xe2\x80\x9cI am optimistic we will identify more people,\xe2\x80\x9d she said. \xe2\x80\x9cBut do I think we will be able to identify every single person? Probably not.\xe2\x80\x9d\nApparently, relatives of the victims have not given up. None of them have told the medical examiner\xe2\x80\x99s office that, after the passage of so much time, they no longer care about matching slivers of remains to their loved ones. \xe2\x80\x9cWe work very closely with the families,\xe2\x80\x9d Dr. Sampson said. \xe2\x80\x9cWe know every family\xe2\x80\x99s wishes as for what they want us to do.\xe2\x80\x9d\nSince 2014, unclaimed remains have rested 70 feet underground in a repository at the \n in Lower Manhattan. Only members of the medical examiner\xe2\x80\x99s office may enter the area (though no laboratory work is done there). Next to the repository is a quiet space known as the reflection room, reserved for Sept. 11 families and their guests. Not surprisingly, the anniversary is a time of pilgrimage there. In a typical month, 20 or so people go to the room. On Sept. 11 alone last year, 65 visited.\nJust about every week, a few families will call the medical examiner\xe2\x80\x99s office with questions, mostly of a technical or administrative nature. Still, often enough, there\xe2\x80\x99s a catch in the caller\xe2\x80\x99s voice or a verbal tic that makes plain how time is an imperfect healer. \xe2\x80\x9cYou can get a sense of despair,\xe2\x80\x9d Dr. Sampson said.\n\xe2\x80\x9cAnd hope,\xe2\x80\x9d she added.\n'
