aS'President Trump didn\xe2\x80\x99t even have the guts to do the job himself. Instead, he hid in the shadows and sent his attorney general, Jeff Sessions, to do the dirty work of telling the country that the administration would no longer shield from deportation 800,000 young undocumented immigrants brought to this country as children.\nMr. Sessions, a longtime anti-immigrant hard-liner, was more than up to the task. In a short, disingenuous speech, he said a program \n \xe2\x80\x94 known as DACA, for Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals \xe2\x80\x94 was a lawless policy that \xe2\x80\x9cyielded terrible humanitarian consequences\xe2\x80\x9d and denied jobs to hundreds of thousands of American citizens. (Mr. Trump echoed these claims in a \n released by the White House.) Mr. Sessions called DACA \xe2\x80\x9can unconstitutional exercise of authority\xe2\x80\x9d and said \xe2\x80\x9cfailure to enforce the laws in the past has put our nation at risk of crime, violence and terrorism.\xe2\x80\x9d\nFalse, false, false and false.\nDACA recipients are not threats to public safety or national security; to the contrary, they must have a nearly spotless record to be eligible in the first place. They do not receive legal status in this country, only a two-year, renewable deferral of deportation along with a work permit and eligibility for other government benefits down the road. And they are not taking jobs from native-born Americans, whose declining levels of employment can be chalked up \n.\nAs for the policy\xe2\x80\x99s legality, there\xe2\x80\x99s no question that the president has the authority to set immigration-enforcement priorities. Presidents of both parties have done that for decades, and President Obama did it by focusing on people with criminal records and not on those brought to this country as children. For most of this latter group, the United States is the only home they\xe2\x80\x99ve ever known. About 9 in 10 are working taxpayers, and deporting them could reduce the gross domestic product \n over the next decade.\nIn short, DACA is morally right, legally sound and fiscally smart policy. It was also the only humane choice Mr. Obama had in the face of Congress\xe2\x80\x99s failure to pass any meaningful immigration reform in the last two decades.\nIf all that weren\xe2\x80\x99t enough, DACA remains overwhelmingly popular among Americans of all political stripes. \n put its approval rating at roughly double that of President Trump himself. Even \n, usually a reliable backer of the Republican legislative agenda, called the decision to end DACA \xe2\x80\x9ccontrary to fundamental American principles.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThe only bad thing that could be said about DACA is that, because it was a presidential memorandum, it was always vulnerable to being undone by a shortsighted administration playing to its base.\nNow that that has happened, 800,000 people \xe2\x80\x94 all of whom gave their personal information and immigration status to the government, believing it would not be used against them \xe2\x80\x94 face the prospect of being shipped back to a country they may have no connection to or even remember.\nThis wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be a concern if Congress had done its job and passed the Dream Act, which would provide a pathway to citizenship for people brought to this country as children, and which has kicked around Capitol Hill for 16 years. Even though it has been stymied mainly by Republican opposition at every turn, it\xe2\x80\x99s still theoretically \n. But there\xe2\x80\x99s little sign the dwindling Republican moderates in Congress have the stomach to confront their party\xe2\x80\x99s nativist core. Mr. Trump called on Congress to act, but didn\xe2\x80\x99t have the courage to tell it what he wanted it to do.\nContrast that with President Obama\xe2\x80\x99s willingness to defend a policy that has always had detractors. \xe2\x80\x9cUltimately, this is about basic decency,\xe2\x80\x9d Mr. Obama wrote \n on Tuesday. \xe2\x80\x9cThis is about whether we are a people who kick hopeful young strivers out of America, or whether we treat them the way we\xe2\x80\x99d want our own kids to be treated.\xe2\x80\x9d\nMr. Trump has no good rejoinder. That\xe2\x80\x99s partly because there isn\xe2\x80\x99t one and partly because, as is so often the case, \n the scope of what he\xe2\x80\x99s done. One would hope that the widespread outrage at Tuesday\xe2\x80\x99s announcement, and the impending suffering of hundreds of thousands of people who\xe2\x80\x99ve done nothing but try to become contributing members of society, might impress it upon him.\n'
