aS'By now, it is a clich\xc3\xa9 to describe The Daily News as the newspaper of New York\xe2\x80\x99s working class. But some clich\xc3\xa9s come to be because they are essentially true. For nearly a century, The News has taken on the world with sleeves-rolled-up sensibilities and New York brass, even amid nose-pressed-against-the glass ogling of celebrities that is a staple of tabloid journalism.\nThe hope here is that the newspaper hangs on to its New York-ness \n, the Chicago-based publisher with a name that sounds straight out of Ogden (\xe2\x80\x9cThe Bronx? No thonx!\xe2\x80\x9d) Nash. Tronc used to be Tribune Publishing. Its present name, a truncation of Tribune online content, reflects an intention to focus more on pixels than on ink-stained wretchedness.\nIn a sense, the purchase represents a reunion for The News. Founded in 1919, it was owned for most of its existence by Tribune, which sold it in 1991 after a bitter strike. The real estate developer and magazine publisher Mortimer Zuckerman bought it in 1993. It gave him a prominent voice in New York civic affairs, beyond what his wealth already provided him. Now that he has given it up at age 80, he may have had his last hurrah as a force in local politics.\nLike most newspapers, The News has struggled in the digital age. It\xe2\x80\x99s easy to forget how it was once a colossus: New York\xe2\x80\x99s picture newspaper, as it used to call itself, unassailable in a tower on Manhattan\xe2\x80\x99s East Side that was the model for The Daily Planet in \xe2\x80\x9cSuperman\xe2\x80\x9d movies. At its peak, in 1947, it had a daily circulation of 2.4 million and nearly twice that on Sundays. Print circulation today has dwindled to the low hundred thousands, and annual losses are believed to be well north of $20 million.\nBut The News still swings for the fences, with jeremiads against political hypocrisy and a renaissance of the sassy front-page headlines that had long been its calling card. In the last two years or so, the \xe2\x80\x9cwood,\xe2\x80\x9d as the headlines on the cover are called in tabloidese, has been conspicuously in-your-face.\nWhen national politicians offered only \xe2\x80\x9cthoughts and prayers\xe2\x80\x9d and nothing about possible gun regulation after the 2015 mass shooting in San Bernardino, Calif., The News\xe2\x80\x99s Page 1 was blunt: \xe2\x80\x9cGod Isn\xe2\x80\x99t Fixing This.\xe2\x80\x9d An NBC interview with the conspiracymonger Alex Jones inspired \xe2\x80\x9cNutwork News.\xe2\x80\x9d New York City Hall\xe2\x80\x99s shrug at pay-to-play allegations led to \xe2\x80\x9cCase of de Blahs.\xe2\x80\x9d\nAnd in 2016 Donald Trump landed on the front page more than once covered in clown makeup. He\xe2\x80\x99s lost the Bozo look as president but not the contumely. The News greeted his withdrawal from the Paris climate accord with \xe2\x80\x9c\n.\xe2\x80\x9d\nAs engaged newspaper readers know, that headline paid homage to a News classic from 1975 when it looked as if Washington would let the city fall into bankruptcy: \xe2\x80\x9c\n.\xe2\x80\x9d The newspaper couldn\xe2\x80\x99t refrain from invoking it as well in January 2016 when Senator Ted Cruz sneered at what he called \xe2\x80\x9cNew York values.\xe2\x80\x9d Accompanying an illustration of the Statue of Liberty giving a one-finger salute, the wood was \xe2\x80\x9cDrop Dead, Ted.\xe2\x80\x9d\nFeeling our own way in the digital world, we can only wish that brashness remains one New York value that Tronc retains. If you will:\nTimes to News:\nStay Bold\n'
