aS'\xe2\x80\x9cWe know very well, more than most, what it means to be deprived of human rights and democratic protection.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThere is truth and gall in these \n, the de facto leader of Myanmar, whose military kept her under house arrest for years until freeing her for good in 2010. Her defiant fight for democracy won her the world\xe2\x80\x99s admiration and a Nobel Peace Prize.\nBut as the Buddhist nation\xe2\x80\x99s persecution of the Muslim Rohingya minority in Rakhine State has reached a peak in the past two weeks, with more than 100,000 people fleeing to Bangladesh, villages burning and untold numbers killed and raped, her acceptance of ethnic cleansing, and her \n, has dashed hope for a just solution.\nHer statement above, made in a phone call to President Recep Tayyip Erdogan of Turkey, was meant as an expression of sincere concern, but was really a rendition of, \xe2\x80\x9cWho are you going to believe, me or your lying eyes?\xe2\x80\x9d\nMyanmar\xe2\x80\x99s military has intensified scorched-earth tactics that were of such \xe2\x80\x9cdevastating cruelty\xe2\x80\x9d last year and early this year that the \n said they most likely constituted \xe2\x80\x9ccrimes against humanity.\xe2\x80\x9d The Rohingya are denied basic rights, including citizenship in the country of their birth. Their persecution has been so egregious that hundreds of thousands have fled or languish in camps.\nTroops began driving out desperate Rohingya after \n by the insurgent Arakan Rohingya Salvation Army on Aug. 25. Since then, Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s military reports that nearly\n have been killed, mostly insurgents, but Rohingya reaching Bangladesh report widespread \n by the military, including deliberate killings of civilians. The insurgents said they were \n to abuses by the military, which reportedly moved \n into the region about a month ago, prompting concern from the United Nations about the Rohingya\xe2\x80\x99s fate.\nThe International Crisis Group \n in December that the root causes of the Rohingya insurgency were the crushing persecution and the cruelty of the military. The solution, the group emphasized, is to work to end discrimination against the Rohingya and to moderate the military\xe2\x80\x99s response, precisely the opposite of what is happening now.\nThe continuing persecution of the Rohingya represents a colossal moral failure on the part of Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s democratically elected government, led by Ms. Aung San Suu Kyi. The military retains considerable power, and she must tread carefully. But that is no excuse for her \n that international aid groups were supporting the insurgency, a charge that puts both aid workers and the people who depend on them in danger. The United Nations\xe2\x80\x99 human rights envoy for Myanmar, Yanghee Lee, said she was \xe2\x80\x9c\n\xe2\x80\x9d by the strict limitations Ms. Aung San Suu Kyi\xe2\x80\x99s government placed on her July visit to the country. The government also \n to United Nations investigators looking into abuses by the military against Rohingya civilians, blocking independent monitors from assessing allegations of serious human rights violations.\nMeanwhile, the United Nations has appealed to Bangladesh not to \n desperate Rohingya reaching its border. India can help by abandoning a merciless \n Rohingya who have taken refuge there. Last week, Pope Francis, who is scheduled to visit Myanmar in November, made a \n for \xe2\x80\x9cmen and women of good will\xe2\x80\x9d to help the Rohingya and \xe2\x80\x9cgive them their full rights.\xe2\x80\x9d The first among these people of good will should be Ms. Aung San Suu Kyi.\n'
