aS'As the daughter of a father from Crete (and of a Cuban-born mother), \n may be familiar with the Greek myth of Sisyphus, doomed for eternity to push a boulder up a hill, only to have it roll back on him every time. Running as a Republican for citywide office in New York is kind of like that \xe2\x80\x94 only maybe more frustrating.\nTrue, two recent mayors ran successfully as Republicans, Rudolph Giuliani and Michael Bloomberg, but the former had broad name recognition from the start, and the latter had tons of money.\nMs. Malliotakis, a young Republican member of the State Assembly from Staten Island\xe2\x80\x99s eastern shore whose district extends into southern Brooklyn, has neither of those advantages in her campaign to displace Bill de Blasio at City Hall. But she has guts. She also has the Republican and Conservative mayoral lines all to herself, so she has been able to concentrate her fire on the Democratic incumbent.\nStaten Island is the only borough in the city that Donald Trump won in 2016, and Ms. Malliotakis says she voted for him. But she now seeks to put daylight between the president and herself and asks to be judged on her merits, which include seven years in the Assembly. In her view, Mr. de Blasio has presided over a deteriorated quality of life, a mass transit system in shambles and an unacceptable municipal policy that protects undocumented immigrants convicted of serious crimes.\nWhether her message can resonate across the heavily Democratic city is a question. But we\xe2\x80\x99re pleased that she is prepared to give her Democratic opponent a lively challenge.\nWhat\xe2\x80\x99s not clear is if she will raise enough money to qualify for city matching funds and for a place in a debate against Mr. de Blasio, assuming he wins his party\xe2\x80\x99s nomination. Should she fall short, we\xe2\x80\x99d encourage the mayor to debate her anyway. The city would be the better for it.\n'
