aS'Jimmy Morales was elected president of Guatemala in 2015 on a promise of stopping the country\xe2\x80\x99s fabled corruption and restoring conservative values. A former television personality widely known for his comic role in the series Moralejas (Morals), Mr. Morales rode popular anger to victory in 2015 as an outsider whose slogan was \xe2\x80\x9cnot corrupt, nor a thief.\xe2\x80\x9d\nBut on Aug. 27, when a United Nations-backed anticorruption unit began getting uncomfortably close to him and his supporters, Mr. Morales \n. Guatemala\xe2\x80\x99s top court \n the order, but the nation still faces a crisis.\nMr. Morales acted out of desperation. Iv\xc3\xa1n Vel\xc3\xa1squez, the respected Colombian prosecutor who heads the unit, the International Commission against Impunity in Guatemala, and the Guatemalan attorney general, Thelma Aldana, had already jailed Morales\xe2\x80\x99s older brother and son. On Aug. 25 they announced they were seeking to strip the president himself of his constitutional immunity in a probe of fishy campaign contributions.\nThe International Commission against Impunity in Guatemala was formed in 2006 at the request of human-rights activists and Guatemalan officials, backed by the United States and other governments, to help Guatemalan prosecutors combat a blight of organized crime and corruption. Much of that has seeped out of criminal networks formed by veterans of the Guatemalan Army that ravaged the country in its long civil war and who then turned the nation into what Amnesty International \n \xe2\x80\x9cCorporate Mafia State.\xe2\x80\x9d Mr. Morales, a social conservative and nationalist, was backed by the National Convergence Front, a party formed by hard-line retired army officers, whose finances are now under investigation.\nPublic fury over revelations of impunity on high overflowed into a protest movement in 2015, forcing the man then president and his vice president to step down. Both are in jail awaiting trial \xe2\x80\x94 the fate Mr. Morales is trying to avoid.\nThe United States, which supported the Guatemalan military during the brutal civil war and is the main political and financial backer of the international commission, should take the leading role, alongside the United Nations, in ensuring that Mr. Morales backs down and lets the investigation lead where it must.\nThe State Department and the United States ambassador to the United Nations, Nikki Haley, were right to \nMr. Morales\xe2\x80\x99s attempt to expel Mr. Vel\xc3\xa1squez. The United Nations secretary general, Ant\xc3\xb3nio Guterres, made clear that \n \xe2\x80\x9cshocked\xe2\x80\x9d by Mr. Morales\xe2\x80\x99s action.\nGuatemala cannot afford to backslide, and Washington must help it stay the course.\n'
