aS'The wrenching shift in the Justice Department\xe2\x80\x99s approach to criminal justice under President Trump is playing out painfully as Chicago tries to rein in a scandalous police culture that tolerated officers routinely abusing and killing residents, particularly African-Americans and Latinos.\nTwo developments last week underlined the need for the firm federal oversight of police misconduct from which Attorney General Jeff Sessions had retreated.\nIn the first, a federal jury handed down a rare criminal conviction of a Chicago policeman. The officer, Marco Proano, was found guilty of using excessive force in violating the civil rights of six black teenagers chased down in a stolen car. He fired 16 shots at them in nine seconds, wounding two as they cowered in the car. A police video was crucial to the conviction, which critics say might have never have happened in city courts, long accused of protecting the police.\nIn the second, the \n, stepped forward and filed an unusual federal lawsuit against Chicago seeking a court-enforced consent decree to reform police training and oversight. The state\xe2\x80\x99s lawsuit would do what the Trump administration had backed away from \xe2\x80\x94 court-enforced controls on the police that the Obama administration engineered through consent decrees in troubled communities from Ferguson, Mo., to Cleveland.\nIn the Obama administration\xe2\x80\x99s waning days, the city agreed to seek a court decree with federal officials. But once Mr. Sessions became attorney general, he spoke skeptically of consent decrees and staunchly defended the police. With Mr. Trump in office, Mayor Rahm Emanuel shifted, insisting the city could achieve reform on its own, overseen by a monitor, not a federal judge.\nIn July, Ms. Madigan wisely \n the idea that any reform would be possible without the muscle of court enforcement. When she announced last week that the state had to act, the mayor was at her side, presumably back on the side of effective reform.\nMs. Madigan asserted that she was compelled to act \xe2\x80\x9cin the absence of a committed Justice Department.\xe2\x80\x9d The goal, she said, is to repair the \xe2\x80\x9cbroken trust\xe2\x80\x9d between the city and black and Hispanic Chicagoans by enforcing \xe2\x80\x9csafe and constitutional police practices.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThe need for overhauling the Chicago force was documented last January in a \n after a yearlong study by Justice investigators that detailed cases of abuse in \xe2\x80\x9ca culture in which officers expect to use force and not be questioned about the need for or propriety of that use.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThe Justice Department has reacted with simplistic echoes of the Trump campaign theme about \xe2\x80\x9crampant" crime and the need for \xe2\x80\x9cproactive policing\xe2\x80\x9d in Chicago. Unfortunately, it did not point to the federal government\xe2\x80\x99s obvious responsibility to help the city protect civil rights.\n'
