aS' If you thought the election of Donald Trump has been a gift for  comedians, think again. \nJust as news media outlets struggle to keep pace with the  controversies and personalities at Trump\xe2\x80\x99s White House, comedy writers, producers, and talk show hosts have scrambled to process material that a year ago appeared to be a comedy gold mine, but which some no longer see as a laughing matter. \n\xe2\x80\x9cPeople say, you comedians must be so happy about Trump,\xe2\x80\x9d said Miles Kahn, writer and producer on Samantha Bee\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9cFull Frontal\xe2\x80\x9d television show on TBS, a unit of Time Warner Inc. \n\xe2\x80\x9cI don\xe2\x80\x99t think any of us are. We\xe2\x80\x99re scared. We get very anxious, we\xe2\x80\x99re kept on edge and when you\xe2\x80\x99re anxious it\xe2\x80\x99s really hard to concentrate and write something funny,\xe2\x80\x9d Kahn said. \n\xe2\x80\x9cFull Frontal\xe2\x80\x9d is competing on Sunday for a variety talk series Emmy - the highest awards in television - in a tight race that includes late-night shows featuring Stephen Colbert, John Oliver and Bill Maher, who all have relentlessly attacked Trump and his policies. \nAsked about the plethora of Trump material, Bee told reporters last week, \xe2\x80\x9cAs citizens, we would actually ask for less. ... We have what we have, so we make what we can out of it.\xe2\x80\x9d \nColbert\xe2\x80\x99s skewering of Trump sent ratings soaring for his \xe2\x80\x9cThe Late Show\xe2\x80\x9d and helped win him the job of hosting Sunday\xe2\x80\x99s prime-time Emmy Awards show. \nAfter its most-watched season in 23 years, sketch show \xe2\x80\x9cSaturday Night Live,\xe2\x80\x9d got 22 Emmy nominations. Melissa McCarthy\xe2\x80\x99s impersonations of former White House press secretary Sean Spicer brought her a guest actress Emmy last Sunday, while Alec Baldwin\xe2\x80\x99s take on Trump and Kate McKinnon\xe2\x80\x99s spoofs of Trump aide Kellyanne Conway are in the race this weekend. \nIn a nation divided by the 2016 presidential election, comedy fills a vital role, even if laughter is sometimes being replaced by outrage, said Dannagal Young, associate professor of communications at the University of Delaware \n\xe2\x80\x9cComedy has a history of making light of tragedy. A lot of people are looking to these shows to make sense of the political world, to find some kinship with other people watching and in recognizing the insanity for what it is,\xe2\x80\x9d Young said. \nTV comics like Bee, Colbert, Oliver and Seth Myers, host of \xe2\x80\x9cLate Night with Seth Meyers,\xe2\x80\x9d have been so hard-hitting that their material sometimes \xe2\x80\x9ccomes close to being didactic, and not cheerful,\xe2\x80\x9d Young said. \nIn August, Meyers called Trump a \xe2\x80\x9clying racist.\xe2\x80\x9d In May, Colbert said Trump has \xe2\x80\x9cmore people marching against (him) than cancer.\xe2\x80\x9d \nWriters on topical shows are constantly being outpaced by news from the White House and Trump\xe2\x80\x99s freewheeling Twitter habit. \n\xe2\x80\x9cPretty much on a weekly basis we are throwing out something that we wanted to talk about. After we have rehearsed the show and are in rewrite, we are constantly checking the news to make sure we are not missing anything,\xe2\x80\x9d said Kahn. \nMeanwhile, shows like White House comedy series \xe2\x80\x9cVeep,\xe2\x80\x9d which is bidding for its a third Emmy, and nefarious Washington drama \xe2\x80\x9cHouse of Cards,\xe2\x80\x9d a contender for best drama series, are in danger of being sidelined. \nYoung questioned whether the once far-fetched premise of such TV shows is still compelling. \n\xe2\x80\x9cI have been a huge fan of \xe2\x80\x98House of Cards,\xe2\x80\x99 but I\xe2\x80\x99ve not even started watching the new season because I don\xe2\x80\x99t have room for the fictional version. I\xe2\x80\x98m already overflowing with the real version,\xe2\x80\x9d she said. \n'
