aS' YuMi the humanoid robot showed no signs of nerves on Tuesday night as it raised its baton to conduct the Lucca Philharmonic orchestra alongside Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli. \nThe two-armed robot, designed by Swiss firm ABB, made its debut at Pisa\xe2\x80\x99s Verdi Theatre to mark the First International Festival of Robotics in the Tuscan city. \n\xe2\x80\x9cWe basically had to find time to understand his movements. When we found the way, everything was pretty easy,\xe2\x80\x9d said the orchestra\xe2\x80\x99s resident conductor, Andrea Colombini. \n\xe2\x80\x9cIt is absolutely fantastic. And the technicians were fantastic just to make everything perfect, especially in the length and in the speed of the gesture, which is very important,\xe2\x80\x9d he said. \nYuMi, whose name is derived from the phrase \xe2\x80\x98you and me\xe2\x80\x99, was taught all the movements by Colombini, who held its arms in rehearsals so the computer could memorize the correct gestures. The robot is not able to improvise and any unexpected change in tempo from the musicians would have been ruinous. \nThe robot conducted three of the 18 pieces performed on Tuesday night, including the famous aria La Donna e\xe2\x80\x99 Mobile, from Verdi\xe2\x80\x99s opera Rigoletto. \n'
