aS' Myanmar leader Aung San Suu Kyi condemned on Tuesday human rights violations in Rakhine state and said violators would be brought to book, but she did not address U.N. accusations of a campaign of ethnic cleansing by the military. \nThe Nobel Peace laureate\xe2\x80\x99s remarks came in her first address to the nation since attacks by Rohingya Muslim insurgents on Aug. 25 sparked a military response that has forced 421,000 Rohingya Muslims into neighboring Bangladesh. \nWestern diplomats and aid officials, hoping for an unequivocal condemnation of violence and hate speech, welcomed the tone of Suu Kyi\xe2\x80\x99s message, but some doubted if she had done enough to deflect global criticism. \nHuman rights group Amnesty International described her speech as \xe2\x80\x9clittle more than a mix of untruths and victim-blaming\xe2\x80\x9d, saying she and her government were \xe2\x80\x9cburying their heads in the sand\xe2\x80\x9d for ignoring the army\xe2\x80\x99s role in the violence. \n\xe2\x80\x9cWe condemn all human rights violations and unlawful violence. We are committed to the restoration of peace and stability and rule of law throughout the state,\xe2\x80\x9d Suu Kyi said in her address in the capital, Naypyitaw. \n\xe2\x80\x9cAction will be taken against all people, regardless of their religion, race and political position, who go against the law of the land and violate human rights,\xe2\x80\x9d she said. \nLong feted in the West as a champion of democracy in the Buddhist-majority country during years of military rule and house arrest, Suu Kyi has faced growing criticism for saying little about abuses faced by the Rohingya. \nThe United States urged Myanmar on Monday to end military operations, grant humanitarian access, and commit to aiding the safe return of civilians to their homes. \nMyanmar\xe2\x80\x99s generals remain in full charge of security and Suu Kyi did not comment on the military or its operation, except to say there had been \xe2\x80\x9cno armed clashes and there have been no clearance operations\xe2\x80\x9d since Sept. 5. \nRohingya refugees arriving in Bangladesh have told of soldiers and Buddhist civilians attacking and burning villages as recently as last Friday. It was not possible to verify their accounts. \nRights monitors and fleeing Rohingya say the army and Rakhine Buddhist vigilantes have mounted a campaign of arson aimed at driving out the Muslim population. The U.N. rights agency said it was \xe2\x80\x9ca textbook example of ethnic cleansing\xe2\x80\x9d. \nMyanmar rejects that, saying its forces are tackling insurgents of the Arakan Rohingya Salvation Army (ARSA), which has claimed responsibility for attacks since October. The government has declared it a terrorist group and accused it of setting the fires and attacking civilians. \nWestern governments that backed Suu Kyi\xe2\x80\x99s campaign against military rule still see her as the best hope for Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s political and economic transition. \nBut she has to avoid angering the powerful army. \nShe also has to avoid alienating her supporters by being seen to take the side of a Muslim minority that enjoys little sympathy in a country that has seen a surge of Buddhist nationalism. \nSome diplomats said she had not squarely addressed the problem of violence in her speech.  \nBut her domestic audience was happy. \nThousands of supporters cheered and let balloons float into the sky in the main city of Yangon as they watched her speech on a big screen. Social media saw a blizzard of posts with the message: \xe2\x80\x9cWe stand with Aung San Suu Kyi\xe2\x80\x9d. \nThe military spokesman was not available for comment. One official familiar with the military\xe2\x80\x99s thinking said it would have no objection to her speech. \nPhil Robertson of Human Rights Watch said satellite images showed about half of all Rohingya villages had been torched and it was time that Suu Kyi, the government and military faced the fact that the security forces \xe2\x80\x9cshoot and kill who they want\xe2\x80\x9d and burn villages. \nAmnesty International said there was \xe2\x80\x9coverwhelming evidence\xe2\x80\x9d the security forces were engaged in ethnic cleansing.  \n\xe2\x80\x9cWhile it was positive to hear Aung San Suu Kyi condemn human rights violations in Rakhine state, she is still silent about the role of the security forces,\xe2\x80\x9d the group said. \n\xe2\x80\x98READY TO EXPLODE\xe2\x80\x99 \nIn Geneva, the head of a U.N. investigation into the violence said his team had heard testimony that suggested Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s security forces may be committing rights violations. \n\xe2\x80\x9cWhat they have come up with reflects in general the reporting of the international media,\xe2\x80\x9d Marzuki Darusman said, referring to a small team of investigators talking to refugees in Bangladesh. \nMyanmar has declined to issue visas to Darusman\xe2\x80\x99s team but he said was more hopeful, following Suu Kyi\xe2\x80\x99s speech in which she spoke of allowing diplomats access to Rakhine state. \nSuu Kyi, 72, said her government had been promoting harmony between the Muslim and largely Buddhist ethnic Rakhine communities. But a government official there did not share her optimism. \n\xe2\x80\x9cThey have no trust for each other,\xe2\x80\x9d the state\xe2\x80\x99s secretary, Tin Maung Swe, told Reuters, adding tension was high. \n\xe2\x80\x9cThe situation is ready to explode.\xe2\x80\x9d \nSuu Kyi said she was committed to recommendations made by an advisory team led by former U.N. secretary-general Kofi Annan, which last month suggested a review of a law that links  citizenship and ethnicity and leaves most Rohingya stateless. \nOn the return of refugees, Suu Kyi said Myanmar was ready to start a verification process and \xe2\x80\x9crefugees from this country will be accepted without any problem\xe2\x80\x9d. \nThe U.N. children\xe2\x80\x99s agency said a quarter of a million children were among the refugees. \n'
