aS'TOKYO \xe2\x80\x94 Pyongyang\xe2\x80\x99s recent missile launch over \n and its underground \n have laid bare Japan\xe2\x80\x99s Achilles\xe2\x80\x99 heel: Our country\xe2\x80\x99s national security policy is still woefully ill equipped for this mounting danger. The \n adopted by the United Nations Security Council on Monday will hardly limit Japan\xe2\x80\x99s exposure.\nNorth Korea\xe2\x80\x99s latest provocations pose an unprecedented threat. Even during the Korean War in the early 1950s, Japan, as a rear support base for United States forces, was somewhat insulated; today, it is in the same theater as South Korea, also on the front lines. Any American military strike against North Korea would likely trigger retaliatory measures against Japan.\nJapan is in a terrible predicament: Highly exposed but with very few options, military or diplomatic, to help itself.\nIts defense ministry plans to \n, to eight, the number of ships equipped with the Aegis missile-defense system. But the new fleet won\xe2\x80\x99t be operational before \n. Even if Japan also acquires the land-based Aegis Ashore system, as it is contemplating doing, none of this additional capacity could offer it enough protection against North Korea\xe2\x80\x99s increasingly lethal missiles \xe2\x80\x94 much less deter North Korea from further developing its own arsenal.\nThis is one reason Itsunori Onodera, the new defense minister, has been making a case for developing Japan\xe2\x80\x99s \n, so that it could strike military bases in North Korea, perhaps even preemptively. But such a move faces numerous obstacles \xe2\x80\x94 financial, tactical and strategic.\nNo budget decision for such capabilities is expected to even be made until at least \n. Acquiring offensive weaponry would require redefining the terms of Japan\xe2\x80\x99s existing security agreement with the United States, which relegates Japan to a purely defensive role and places all responsibility for any offensive action solely with America.\nIn the face of these constraints, some \n and \n in Washington are arguing that Japan, as well as South Korea, might, and perhaps \n, consider acquiring nuclear weapons themselves.\nThe idea is a nonstarter. According to \n conducted in June and July, only 9 percent of Japanese respondents think Japan should acquire nuclear weapons. (About 67 percent of South Koreans polled said that South Korea should get such weapons.) The nuclearization of Japan \xe2\x80\x94 or South Korea \xe2\x80\x94 would undermine nonproliferation efforts, as well as validate North Korea\xe2\x80\x99s nuclear brinkmanship to date.\nGiven the difficulties of developing an independent military capability, Tokyo has no choice but to pursue a diplomatic solution with the help of other states \xe2\x80\x94 even though several multilateral efforts have failed in the past and bilateral relations between some of the main players today arguably are more fraught than ever.\nTensions are mounting between the United States and China, for example, over dominance in the South China Sea. South Korea\xe2\x80\x99s decision to deploy the missile-defense system known as Thaad to protect itself from North Korea has \n Beijing, which says the system is in fact designed to track missiles from China.\nRelations between Tokyo and Seoul have long been uneasy, largely because of unresolved issues from Japan\xe2\x80\x99s occupation of the Korean Peninsula in the 1930s and 1940s, including about so-called comfort women, Korean women who were coerced or compelled into having sex with Japanese soldiers. And the new South Korean president, Moon Jae-in, appears to be taking a firmer stand on that question than his predecessor, who signed an agreement with Japan in 2015 hoping to finally settle the matter. It is now very difficult to imagine, for example, that Japan\xe2\x80\x99s Self-Defense Forces could ever \n, even to assist with, say, an evacuation after an attack by North Korea.\nAt the same time, however, as the threat from Pyongyang becomes more ominous, the pressing need for an effective response may suggest, even create, new diplomatic opportunities.\nPrime Minister Shinzo Abe of Japan and President Trump seem to have quickly developed an intimate working relationship, and that \xe2\x80\x94 along with South Korea\xe2\x80\x99s moves to strengthen its security ties with the United States \xe2\x80\x94 may allow for more effective cooperation among the three countries, despite difficulties between Japan and South Korea. This trilateralism, in turn, could form the basis for five-party talks including China and Russia, and eventually lead to the resumption of negotiations with Pyongyang as well.\nThe U.N. Security Council\xe2\x80\x99s decision to cap North Korea\xe2\x80\x99s oil imports, though a watered-down version of the penalties sought by the United States government, was significant nonetheless. For one thing, it was a reminder that coordinated action with China and Russia, which have been wary of imposing more sanctions against Pyongyang, is possible.\nOn this front, too, North Korea\xe2\x80\x99s recent brinkmanship may have unexpectedly paved the way for new (if slim) possibilities for cooperation. Mr. Abe and President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia seem to have developed an effective line of communication, including on intractable-seeming issues, like the status of \n in the Pacific. And the chances for at least some measure of rapprochement between Japan and China may be growing. Building bridges with Beijing remains a loaded notion for many Japanese people, but Mr. Abe now has more clout and political capital to try, in the name of protecting Japan against the more immediate threat posed by North Korea.\nThe recent escalation of the North Korea crisis seems to have validated Mr. Abe\xe2\x80\x99s controversial efforts to strengthen Japan\xe2\x80\x99s defense posture. The Japanese public is now \n to adopting a tougher stance. The new leader of the opposition Democratic Party, Seiji Maehara, is a hawk, and under his leadership the party, traditionally an advocate of pacifism, is likely to support, if perhaps reluctantly, the Abe administration\xe2\x80\x99s hard-nosed approach to security.\nThere is no viable military solution to the North Korea crisis. Japan, like the other main parties, must make the most of the slivers of opportunity created by the escalating threat to renew efforts at finding a multilateral diplomatic solution.\n'
