aS'After the white-nationalist rally in Charlottesville, Va., last month where a man drove a car into a crowd, killing a counter-demonstrator, the American neo-Nazi website The Daily Stormer published a long, hate-riddled post mocking the victim.\nOutcry over the article led its domain registrar, GoDaddy, \n. The site then registered with Google, which also quickly canceled its hosting. But it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t until Cloudflare, a website security and performance service, dropped the site as a client that The Daily Stormer truly lost its ability to stay online.\nBecause of the precise nature of Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s business, and the scarcity of competitors, its role censoring internet speech is not just new, it\xe2\x80\x99s \nWhat makes Cloudflare an essential part of the internet is \n from barraging clients\xe2\x80\x99 websites with requests that take them offline. Cloudflare is one of the few companies in the world that provide this kind of reliable protection. If you don\xe2\x80\x99t want your website to get taken down by extortionists, jokers, political opposition or hackers, you have to hire Cloudflare or one of its very few competitors.\nGenerally speaking, there are two kinds of corporate players on the internet: companies that build infrastructure through which content flows, and companies that seek to curate content and create a community.\nInternet service providers like Verizon and Comcast, domain name servers, web hosts and security services providers like Cloudflare are all the former \xe2\x80\x94 or the \xe2\x80\x9cpipe.\xe2\x80\x9d They typically don\xe2\x80\x99t look at the content their clients and customers are putting up, they just give them the means to do it and let it flow. Social media platforms like Facebook are the latter. They encourage their users to create, share and engage with content \xe2\x80\x94 so they look at content all the time and decide whether they want to allow hateful material like that of neo-Nazis to stay up.\nWhile there have long been worries about internet service providers favoring access to some content over others, there has been less concern about companies further along the pipeline holding an internet on/off switch. In large part, this is because at other points in the pipeline, users have choice. Private companies can make their own rules, and consumers can choose among them. If GoDaddy won\xe2\x80\x99t register your domain, you can go to Bluehost or thousands of other companies.\nBut the fewer choices you have for the infrastructure you need to stay online, the more serious the consequences when companies refuse service. This is why Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s decision to drop The Daily Stormer is so significant. Denying security service to one Nazi website seems fine now, but what if Cloudflare started suspending service for a political candidate that its chief executive didn\xe2\x80\x99t like?\nWith this move, Cloudflare is wading into the business of evaluating the content of its clients \xe2\x80\x94 something sites like Facebook and Twitter have been wrestling with for years, leading them to develop complex rules and procedures that govern what users are and are not allowed to post. Most agree that it\xe2\x80\x99s appropriate for social media companies to take down certain kinds of content \xe2\x80\x94 that\xe2\x80\x99s how they ensure our newsfeeds aren\xe2\x80\x99t full of pornography or violence. But that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t mean we don\xe2\x80\x99t want that type of content to be able to exist \n on the internet. Ensuring that sites like Cloudflare remain content-neutral might be necessary to guarantee that.\nOne of the additional difficulties with Cloudflare is that it is not so much a piece of pipe as it is a service. Specifically, it is a paid-for-protection service. Having to hire Cloudflare to protect your website is like having to hire security to protect you from attackers when you speak in the public square. If that security service is the only one in town, and you\xe2\x80\x99ll be silenced if you try to speak without it, maybe that security service shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t pick and choose whom it protects. While regulation should not be done lightly or broadly, there\xe2\x80\x99s a case to be made that we should treat Cloudflare more like the police, who are supposed to equally protect all members of the public.\nLast week, Matthew Prince, Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s chief executive, acknowledged how much power his company has, and what\xe2\x80\x99s at stake. \xe2\x80\x9cThe internet is a really important resource for everyone,\xe2\x80\x9d he said in an interview with \n, \xe2\x80\x9cbut there\xe2\x80\x99s a very limited set of companies that control it and there\xe2\x80\x99s such little accountability to us that it really is quite a dangerous thing.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThis is the most terrifying realization surrounding Cloudflare\xe2\x80\x99s removal of a site from the internet: There\xe2\x80\x99s a lack of accountability present at every part of the pipeline and on platforms. The people who run these companies are not elected officials, yet we still expect them to safeguard our basic liberties while also meeting our cultural expectations. For the most part they do: both because it\xe2\x80\x99s good business to meet the expectations of their users, and because most have praiseworthy goals of corporate responsibility. Beyond these minor checks on these companies\xe2\x80\x99 power, we as users have no way to ensure they meet our needs \xe2\x80\x94 and we have no idea what site they\xe2\x80\x99ll take down next.\n'
