aS'Ben Shapiro is a 33-year-old who \n small government, religious liberty and free-market economics and opposes identity politics, abortion and Donald Trump. He is, in other words, that wildly exotic creature: a political conservative.\nYou\xe2\x80\x99d think that the cosmopolitan denizens of the San Francisco Bay Area would have encountered a few, if not in the form of an uncle at Thanksgiving, then perhaps in, I don\xe2\x80\x99t know, a field trip down to Orange County. But to judge from the pre-emptive reaction to Mr. Shapiro\xe2\x80\x99s speech scheduled for this Thursday at the University of California, Berkeley, you\xe2\x80\x99d be mistaken.\nLast week Paul Alivisatos, the university\xe2\x80\x99s executive vice chancellor and provost, sent out a grave \n to students and faculty members. \xe2\x80\x9cWe are deeply concerned about the impact some speakers may have on individuals\xe2\x80\x99 sense of safety and belonging,\xe2\x80\x9d he wrote, encouraging his readers to avail themselves of campus counseling services. \xe2\x80\x9cNo one should be made to feel threatened or harassed simply because of who they are or for what they believe.\xe2\x80\x9d\nMr. Alivisatos wasn\xe2\x80\x99t referring to the various threats against Mr. Shapiro that you might imagine would be his chief concern: When the right-wing provocateur Milo Yiannopoulos visited campus in February, the resulting protests caused $100,000 in \n. This time around, the activist group Refuse Fascism, which has \n the left-wing extremist \n movement as \xe2\x80\x9ccourageous,\xe2\x80\x9d has taken the lead in condemning Mr. Shapiro\xe2\x80\x99s speech, calling him a \xe2\x80\x9cfascist\xe2\x80\x9d on campus fliers and declaring in a Facebook post that his goal was to \xe2\x80\x9cspread ugly fascist views dressed up in slick-talking \xe2\x80\x98intellectual\xe2\x80\x99 garb.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThe group has \n a rally during Mr. Shapiro\xe2\x80\x99s talk. It\xe2\x80\x99s no wonder the university has promised a \xe2\x80\x9cclosed perimeter\xe2\x80\x9d around the building where he is set to speak and an \xe2\x80\x9cincreased and highly visible police presence.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThere\xe2\x80\x99s no question that Ben Shapiro loves to provoke college students. He \n a diaper to a campus speech to offer to \xe2\x80\x9cself-indulgent pathetic children who can\xe2\x80\x99t handle anyone with an opposing point of view.\xe2\x80\x9d In another, while entertaining a question from a young woman who called for greater sensitivity toward transgender people, he \n: \xe2\x80\x9cIf I call you a moose are you suddenly a moose?\xe2\x80\x9d\nYet this sharp-tongued Never Trumper was also, according to the Anti-Defamation League, by far the \n Jewish journalist of 2016 \xe2\x80\x94 quite a distinction when you think about the kind of vitriol that gushed forth this past year on platforms like Twitter. Those attacks came from the alt-right, which called Mr. Shapiro a \xe2\x80\x9cChrist killer\xe2\x80\x9d and far worse. When his son was born, the trolls called the baby a \xe2\x80\x9cnewborn cockroach\xe2\x80\x9d and suggested that the entire Shapiro family head to the gas chambers.\nLet\xe2\x80\x99s hope the protest against this \xe2\x80\x9cfascist\xe2\x80\x9d who has been the regular target of actual ones doesn\xe2\x80\x99t result in any violence. But the brouhaha over Ben Shapiro is significant not because of what might go down Thursday at Berkeley, but because it is a perfect exhibition of a much broader phenomenon increasingly apparent in the wake of the Charlottesville, Va., demonstrations last month: the sloppy conflation between actual white supremacists and, well, run-of-the-mill conservatives, libertarians and classical liberals whose main beef is with some on the left who seem like they\xe2\x80\x99d rather do without the First Amendment.\nWhat happened at the Unite the Right protest in Charlottesville was the real article: a gathering of proud white supremacists, neo-Nazis and fellow travelers brandishing torches and flags and a Dodge Challenger in order to terrify residents, kill a counterprotester and injure 19 others.\nLater in August, however, there were long-planned free-speech protests across the country that had nothing to do with that ugly demonstration. Liberty Weekend in the Bay Area was one of them.\nThe demonstration was organized by the leader of a right-wing group Patriot Prayer, Joey Gibson, who advertised the event this way: \xe2\x80\x9cNo extremists will be allowed in. No Nazis, Communist, K.K.K., Antifa, white supremacist, I.E., or white nationalists. This is an opportunity for moderate Americans to come in with opposing views. We will not allow the extremists to tear apart this country. Specifically, Richard Spencer and Nathan Damigo will not be welcome.\xe2\x80\x9d\nPerhaps one of the reasons Mr. Gibson had to make his intentions \n is that in the past his events have attracted just the kind of people who are fans of anti-Semites and racists like Mr. Spencer: the \xe2\x80\x9cWestern-chauvinist\xe2\x80\x9d \n; the alt-right group \n, or I.E., which was founded last year by Mr. Damigo; plus fans of conspiracy theorists like Alex Jones.\nMr. Gibson had also assembled a list of speakers that included, according to the group\xe2\x80\x99s \n, only one white male. The others were Hispanic, black, Asian, Samoan and Muslim; two were women. Mr. Gibson himself is half-Japanese.\nYou wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t have known any of this though, if you\xe2\x80\x99d listened to news reports or politicians, as Matt Labash pointed out in his \n about the event in The Weekly Standard.\nRepresentative Nancy Pelosi \n the event \xe2\x80\x9ca white supremacist rally\xe2\x80\x9d and criticized the National Park Service for giving Patriot Prayer a permit to gather in Crissy Field, not far from the Golden Gate Bridge: \xe2\x80\x9cThey\xe2\x80\x99re going to give it as a venue to Nazis and white nationalists.\xe2\x80\x9d\nSenator Dianne Feinstein lent an amen with her own letter to the Park Service voicing her \n that the park would \xe2\x80\x9cbe used as a venue for Patriot Prayer\xe2\x80\x99s incitement, hate and intimidation.\xe2\x80\x9d\nState Senator Scott Wiener \n Patriot Prayer an \xe2\x80\x9cextremist group,\xe2\x80\x9d insisting that it was \xe2\x80\x9cnot interested in simply exercising free speech\xe2\x80\x9d with its event, but rather in creating \xe2\x80\x9ca volatile, chaotic, violent tinderbox.\xe2\x80\x9d\nSan Francisco\xe2\x80\x99s mayor, Ed Lee, asked residents to avoid \xe2\x80\x9cengaging with members of Patriot Prayer\xe2\x80\x9d lest anyone \xe2\x80\x9cdignify their message of hate and their mission of division in our city of love of compassion.\xe2\x80\x9d\nIn the end, however, the \n didn\xe2\x80\x99t emanate from Mr. Gibson\xe2\x80\x99s camp, but from antifa groups that \n to kick some fascist butt. Meantime, Mr. Gibson said things like \xe2\x80\x9cmoderates have to come together.\xe2\x80\x9d Strange words for an accused fascist. But when mainstream politicians are engaging in \n, should Mr. Gibson\xe2\x80\x99s branding as such come as any surprise?\nOne of my favorite things on YouTube is the famous 1965 debate between James Baldwin and William F. Buckley at Cambridge University. Baldwin wiped the floor with Buckley before the all-white British audience \xe2\x80\x94 the yeas \n the nays 540 to 160 on the proposition \xe2\x80\x9cThe American dream is at the expense of the American Negro.\xe2\x80\x9d\nCan anyone doubt that if Buckley tried to argue the same point today he would have been pelted with a \n, or shouted down, or \n or worse? Perhaps he would have just avoided the tiresome indignity by canceling the talk.\nWatch it. You\xe2\x80\x99ll be grateful he didn\xe2\x80\x99t.\n'
