aS'Nineteen sixty-seven may have been a brutal year in Vietnam \xe2\x80\x94 tens of thousands of Vietnamese and more than 11,000 Americans lost their lives in what increasingly looked like an endless war \xe2\x80\x94 but it was also, the United Nations decreed more hopefully, International Tourist Year.\nThe National Tourist Office of the Republic of Vietnam \xe2\x80\x94 yes, the American-backed South Vietnamese government maintained a tourism office during the war \xe2\x80\x94 issued a cheerful guidebook touting the conflict-ravaged country as an enticing destination. With its sophisticated mountain resorts, fine white beaches, extensive hunting reserves and numerous other attractions, Vietnam was \xe2\x80\x9crapidly becoming a \xe2\x80\x98must see\xe2\x80\x99 for thousands of foreign tourists,\xe2\x80\x9d it maintained.\nThe claim was, of course, ludicrous. Few tourists were making the trip to Vietnam by 1967, and those who did largely stuck to the capital. \xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s rather risky to go far from Saigon,\xe2\x80\x9d the chief tourism official conceded that spring. Yet the guidebook\xe2\x80\x99s publication, as bizarre as it may seem, reminds us of the extent to which tourism was about far more than travel. For both the Republic of Vietnam and the United States, tourism contained an important political dimension.\nThere was a time, in the late 1950s and early \xe2\x80\x9960s, when Vietnam did attract thousands of pleasure-seeking visitors. Holiday magazine profiled the country in 1957, and Travel magazine did a piece on Vietnam\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9cspectacular\xe2\x80\x9d sites two years later. By the early 1960s, South Vietnam was enjoying tens of thousands of foreign visitors. This was great news for both Washington and Saigon.\nNot only would tourism promote the economic development and foreign-currency earnings that were so crucial to the South Vietnamese nation-building project, but, officials hoped, it also could generate positive views of the Republic of Vietnam and its contribution to Washington\xe2\x80\x99s Cold War mission. This was true of both the in-country experiences of foreign tourists as well as the ideologically inflected literature they relied on to mediate their travel.\nIn the years following the 1954 Geneva Accords that temporarily divided Vietnam, the South Vietnamese authorities, using tourism as one of the tools in their soft-power arsenal, attempted to overcome the crisis of legitimacy that imperiled their fledgling state. The republic\xe2\x80\x99s first president, Ngo Dinh Diem, was deeply unpopular, but both independent and government-produced tourism publications overlooked his political shortcomings in favor of a Cold War narrative that portrayed Diem as an effective nation-builder and one of the free world\xe2\x80\x99s greatest assets.\nThe Communist hordes in Vietnam, one American guidebook insisted, sought nothing less than \xe2\x80\x9cto enslave the entire population.\xe2\x80\x9d Fortunately, Diem \xe2\x80\x94 \xe2\x80\x9ca man of great vigor, vision and iron will\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x94 was there to stop them, \xe2\x80\x9cOlson\xe2\x80\x99s Orient Guide\xe2\x80\x9d continued.\nThe tourism publications of the 1950s and \xe2\x80\x9960s consistently touted the American-backed government\xe2\x80\x99s alleged democratic credentials while delegitimizing the Vietnamese revolution as naked Communist aggression. The southern republic was thus \xe2\x80\x9cFree Vietnam,\xe2\x80\x9d according to Travel magazine. The Democratic Republic of Vietnam, conversely, was the \xe2\x80\x9cCommunist-dominated\xe2\x80\x9d or \xe2\x80\x9cCommunist-held North.\xe2\x80\x9d\nNone of this is particularly surprising in the context of Cold War ideology. But it underscores a largely overlooked facet of the Vietnam War: Tourism and its attendant literature played a surprising yet significant role in wartime propaganda. Not only did this literature frame the political unrest in the South for travelers hungry for information, but it was also disseminated outside Southeast Asia. The \xe2\x80\x9cGuide to Viet-Nam\xe2\x80\x9d published by South Vietnam\xe2\x80\x99s Washington embassy, for example, was ostensibly created for tourists and, generously sprinkled with attractive photographs, included all sorts of information on the points of interest, festivals and Vietnamese culture certain to appeal to foreign visitors. Yet the 40-page guide, which touted the \xe2\x80\x9cfree democratic system in the South\xe2\x80\x9d and the instrumental role it played in \xe2\x80\x9cthe ideological contest between the Communist and the Free Worlds,\xe2\x80\x9d was also distributed to hundreds of American schoolteachers for use in their classrooms.\nThe growing importance of tourism publications was consistent with the diplomatic significance the United States attached to international travel in the 1950s, as the jet age and the growth of the middle class enabled hundreds of thousands of Americans to begin venturing abroad. Most of them knew little of the political complexities and nuances of decolonization, making the travel literature on which they relied that much more important. It would explain the world they were seeing and experiencing. For most tourist publications, the leftist revolutions springing up in Asia, Africa and Latin America became instances of Communist subversion, and Communism, Americans were told, required a \xe2\x80\x9cfree world\xe2\x80\x9d response.\nThe growth of international travel in the 1950s also meant ideologically preparing Americans to serve as unofficial ambassadors for their nation. The Eisenhower administration underscored this obligation by issuing a presidential letter to all American passport holders in 1957. It stressed tourists\xe2\x80\x99 role in helping to \xe2\x80\x9cmold the reputation of our country,\xe2\x80\x9d bringing \xe2\x80\x9cassurance to the people you meet that the United States is a friendly nation and one dedicated to the search for world peace and to the promotion of the well-being and security of the community of nations.\xe2\x80\x9d\nBut tourism did not benefit only Washington. For the government in Saigon, the positive experiences of American tourists and the stories they subsequently told about their visits could be a diplomatic boon. As a motto of the National Tourist Office put it, tourism would \xe2\x80\x9cmake the country better known and thus better loved.\xe2\x80\x9d\nFor a time, things seemed to go as planned. The American actor George C. Scott, for example, went to Vietnam in 1965 and meditated on his experience in Esquire magazine. \xe2\x80\x9cWhether we like it or not, we are and have been for years at war with International Communism,\xe2\x80\x9d he wrote. \xe2\x80\x9cThe Vietnamese conflict is a unique and necessary phase of that larger war, the consequences of which may not be sidestepped, or shirked, or diplomatized under a polished table.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThe Follett family of Oak Park, Ill., made the trip the following year. \xe2\x80\x9cWe came because we wanted to see what was happening in Vietnam ourselves,\xe2\x80\x9d Dwight Follett told Saturday Review. \xe2\x80\x9cIn the United States, everything we read is either black or white.\xe2\x80\x9d His assessment? \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m coming out of this more a hawk than a dove. We must help these people.\xe2\x80\x9d\nBy 1967, with the war\xe2\x80\x99s continuing escalation, the flow of tourists into the country, already seriously diminished, had nearly dried up. The publisher Fodor\xe2\x80\x99s, whose annual guidebooks proved some of the most popular of the mid-20th century, explained why. After offering tepid encouragement about seeing Vietnam through 1966, its 1967 prognosis was grim: \xe2\x80\x9cThis divided nation, torn by war for twenty years, is the most dangerous country in the world for today\xe2\x80\x99s visitor.\xe2\x80\x9d Its advice? \xe2\x80\x9cDon\xe2\x80\x99t ever yield to the temptation\xe2\x80\x9d to go.\nMost didn\xe2\x80\x99t. More than 34,000 foreign civilians did arrive in Vietnam in 1967, but they were almost exclusively businesspeople, journalists, contractors and government officials. Actual sightseers numbered, at most, in the low hundreds. And they largely remained in Saigon. This was quite a departure from the early years of the nation-building project.\nAs the 1960s folded into the 1970s, things only got worse. The ideological appeal of tourism seemed a thing of the past. Indeed, by 1973, the year the last American combat forces withdrew, the director of the National Tourist Office took to openly encouraging the prostitution of Vietnamese women. \xe2\x80\x9cSoon I will send up a proposal for \xe2\x80\x98sex tourism,\xe2\x80\x99 \xe2\x80\x9d he told an American reporter. \xe2\x80\x9cMany people want to visit Vietnam not to see the mountains or the shopping but to try, just once, our girls.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThis was the moral abyss into which Vietnamese tourism, like the American war it served, had sunk. It\xe2\x80\x99s little wonder that the revolution prevailed.\n'
