aS'Is it permissible to take a selfie in front of the Kaaba during hajj? With spotty internet, I was unable to Google the answer. Forced to call an audible fatwa, I decided, \xe2\x80\x9cYes, if indeed my intention is pure.\xe2\x80\x9d\nFourteen hundred years ago, the Prophet Muhammad and his companions definitely didn\xe2\x80\x99t have to decide between Clarendon and Gingham filters to document the hajj pilgrimage that is recreated by Muslims each year. But then again, they didn\xe2\x80\x99t have Instagram as I did when I went to Mecca to satisfy the pillar of my faith during the last days of August and the beginning of September. They didn\xe2\x80\x99t have access to the air-conditioned tents that I used for shelter. And when they gazed at the Kaaba \xe2\x80\x94 the austere black cube that represents God\xe2\x80\x99s house on earth \xe2\x80\x94 it certainly wasn\xe2\x80\x99t dwarfed, as it is now, by \n that the Saudi government added to the landscape in 2012.\nAwe-struck by the privilege of participating in this tradition while often agitated by the contradictions that surround it today, I made sense of the experience by sharing it \xe2\x80\x94 filtering the pilgrimage through the lens of my smartphone.\nThe most painful aspect of hajj wasn\xe2\x80\x99t the physical toll that came with navigating cramped space with my two million diverse fellow pilgrims, or the intense spiritual concentration. It wasn\xe2\x80\x99t the hiking-induced blisters and chafing. It was witnessing the erasure and razing of my religion\xe2\x80\x99s culture, history and narrative by the House of Saud.\nThe Saudi royal family follows the revisionist and extreme ideology of Wahhabism, which preaches an interpretation of strict monotheism that is often at odds with centuries of theological scholarship. They consider veneration and respect of most holy sites and visitations of graves as a form of idolatry.\nThat explains why, in their country, while the Prophet Muhammad\xe2\x80\x99s mosque and courtyard in Medina are spacious, cooled and immaculate, Jannat al-Baqi \xe2\x80\x94 a graveyard directly across from the green dome housing the remains of thousands of Islam\xe2\x80\x99s luminaries \xe2\x80\x94 looks like a set from \xe2\x80\x9cMad Max: Fury Road.\xe2\x80\x9d There are no tombstones, just slabs of rock sticking out like middle fingers from the dirt. If you linger too long to pay respects or offer a prayer, the mutawwa \xe2\x80\x94 religious police \xe2\x80\x94 rush you along. When you ask them who\xe2\x80\x99s buried here, they answer, \xe2\x80\x9cAllah knows best,\xe2\x80\x9d although they know the truth: the daughter of the prophet, his family members and some of his most loyal companions.\nMy friends and I spent hours at the prophet\xe2\x80\x99s tomb and the rawdah \xe2\x80\x94 a space between his original pulpit and grave considered by Muslims to be some of the hottest spiritual real estate on earth. The moving experience was tempered by the awareness that most Muslims long to offer their \xe2\x80\x9csalaams\xe2\x80\x9d (prayers of peace) to the prophet, but cannot afford to visit his mosque. Also, women are often unable to properly perform the \xe2\x80\x9cziyarat\xe2\x80\x9d (religious visitation) there because they\xe2\x80\x99re allowed only limited access.\nIn Mecca, I hiked nearly an hour under the remorseless afternoon sun to visit the Cave of Hira, where the prophet is believed to have received his first revelation: \xe2\x80\x9cRecite!\xe2\x80\x9d There are no golden signs, air-conditioning, wheelchair ramps or video presentations here. The austere cave used to offer a clear line of sight to the Kaaba, but now the view is now obscured by that monstrous, $15 billion, Saudi-government-funded clock tower and the accompanying world\xe2\x80\x99s tallest hotel.\nThat tableau is a perfect symbol of the strained marriage between the house of God \xe2\x80\x94 the Kaaba, in Mecca \xe2\x80\x94 and the House of Saud, which controls everything related to the sacred mosques. In adherence to the reactionary religious ideology it embraces, the government has allowed the prophet\xe2\x80\x99s house to fall into decrepitude. It has flattened the home of his first wife, Khadija, and installed public toilets where it used to stand. But it has no objection to the construction of extravagant hotels not far away.\nThese government\xe2\x80\x99s conflicting values were on display wherever I looked: While non-Muslims are forbidden from even entering Mecca, everyone is free to eat American Hardee\xe2\x80\x99s hamburgers or KFC fried chicken, or buy a Rolex watch across from the Kaaba. It\xe2\x80\x99s forbidden to excessively venerate the prophet and his companions, but there\xe2\x80\x99s no problem with the giant posters of King Abdulaziz, King Salman and his son, Crown Prince Muhammad bin Salman, that are all around town.\nBut whenever I found myself lamenting the ugliness and hypocrisy of these elements of my journey, the people I met reminded me why I was there, with displays of untarnished spirituality. In the prophet\xe2\x80\x99s mosque, local people brought bread, dates and milk to feed fasting pilgrims. Children begged me to eat from the plates they had prepared, hoping to gain some of the blessings. In the desert plain of Arafat, east of Mecca, I walked with nearly two million pilgrims to the Mount of Mercy. Men and women offered whatever they had: water, food, ice cream, a helping hand for a wheelchair-user. They shared the shade under their umbrellas, and sometimes even the clothes off their back with fellow pilgrims. We were united in a shared journey: seeking to find forgiveness, mercy and salvation.\nIt made sense to invite fellow Muslims and friends along for a view of this often-schizophrenic experience, unfiltered through Wahhabi propaganda. While I initially worried it might distract me from my prayer, sharing the photos and Facebook Live videos made hajj a communal experience, in the most modern way possible.\nIn Mecca and Medina, often through my camera\xe2\x80\x99s lens, I looked up at the heavens and at the shiny buildings, but I also looked around me and engaged with a community of believers \xe2\x80\x94 some of them with me on ground, and some of them looking at screens on the other side of the world. That\xe2\x80\x99s where I found God \xe2\x80\x94 and beauty \xe2\x80\x94 in all its glorious contradictions.\n'
