aS'PHNOM PENH, Cambodia \xe2\x80\x94 Kem Sokha, the leader of the opposition Cambodia National Rescue Party (C.N.R.P.), was \n during the early hours of Sept. 3, reportedly without a warrant and in violation of his parliamentary immunity. Dozens of police officers surrounded his home in Phnom Penh, while a group of armed men forced their way inside.\nHe has since been charged with treason \xe2\x80\x94 and with \n with foreigners to overthrow the Hun Sen government \xe2\x80\x94 based on a 2013 speech in which he described wanting to bring peaceful, democratic change to Cambodia and receiving advice from American experts. On Monday, during a session that the C.N.R.P. boycotted, the National Assembly \n to allow the case against Mr. Kem Sokha to proceed, implicitly lifting his immunity.\nGovernment-aligned media have named more purported participants in the spurious plot, intensifying the already palpable fear that anyone in our party, or anyone seen as supporting it, could be the government\xe2\x80\x99s next target. Several legislators who are senior members of the C.N.R.P. have left the country after being called co-conspirators.\nThe independent media, for their part, are being wiped out. The government is invoking specious tax bills or contractual violations to muzzle outlets like The Cambodia Daily, Voice of America, Radio Free Asia and Voice of Democracy, which have a history of reporting on controversial issues like expropriation, deforestation and government corruption.\nLast month, the local office of the National Democratic Institute, an American pro-democracy nonprofit organization, was abruptly \n. Other NGOs are being threatened or bullied into silence.\nOver the past several years, a spate of laws has been passed \xe2\x80\x94 over objections from the C.N.R.P. and civil society groups \xe2\x80\x94 restricting the legitimate activities of political parties, trade unions and NGOs and associations. The assassination of the outspoken political analyst Kem Ley over a year ago has yet to be properly investigated.\nThe ruling Cambodian People\xe2\x80\x99s Party is cracking down ahead of the general election scheduled for next year because it fears for its prospects then. In the \n in 2013, the C.P.P. won 68 seats in the National Assembly \xe2\x80\x94 down from 90 \xe2\x80\x94 and the C.N.R.P. won 55, a record for an opposition party. We also made impressive gains in local elections in June, winning control of \n \xe2\x80\x94 up from the combined 40 communes (out of 1,633) won in the 2012 local elections by the two opposition parties that later merged to form the C.N.R.P.\nThese results may seem modest, but they are remarkable considering the C.P.P.\xe2\x80\x99s lock on state resources and the increasingly repressive political climate in Cambodia. And they prove that the C.N.R.P. appeals not only to the educated and the urban, but also to the rural poor, long the beneficiaries of the C.P.P.\xe2\x80\x99s vast patronage networks.\nIf convicted of treason, Mr. Kem Sokha faces up to 30 years in prison. Under recent revisions to the law on political parties \xe2\x80\x94 which ban parties from having leaders with criminal records \xe2\x80\x94 the C.N.R.P. would then be dissolved. These legal changes have already forced the C.N.R.P.\xe2\x80\x99s former president, Sam Rainsy, to resign because he is the subject of several (dubious) defamation cases.\nThe government\xe2\x80\x99s game is transparent. If Mr. Kem Sokha stays at the helm of the C.N.R.P., the party risks being dismantled. If he steps down, more bogus charges will be brought against our next leader \xe2\x80\x94 and then the next. Succumbing to the C.P.P.\xe2\x80\x99s threat to disband us unless we abandon our current leadership would be a grave political error. We refuse to be complicit in this assault on democracy.\nC.N.R.P. members and lawmakers have weathered various onslaughts before, including arbitrary arrests and beatings at the hands of the prime minister\xe2\x80\x99s \n. We have stood our ground out of faith in the power of the democratic process. Should our party be dissolved, the next general election would be a farce, and the next government, a fraud.\nOur resolve is steadfast, but we need all the help we can get. We have been heartened by the support of governments, lawmakers and organizations around the world \xe2\x80\x94 the \n, \n, \n, \n \xe2\x80\x94 that have criticized Mr. Kem Sokha\xe2\x80\x99s unjustified arrest. Yet we need concrete help, too.\nThe Hun Sen government may feel emboldened to crack down on all forms of opposition, even at the risk of alienating its partners in the West, because China has lavished military aid and investments on Cambodia in recent years: According to an \n published in The Economist earlier this year, Chinese money accounted for 70 percent of total industrial investment in Cambodia between 2011 and 2015. But Western countries still have leverage here.\nBetween about 30 percent and 40 percent of the Cambodian government\xe2\x80\x99s budget is still covered by foreign development assistance, including from European Union countries, the United States, Canada, Australia, Japan and South Korea. Cambodia also benefits from preferential trade terms, such as most-favored-nation status with the United States and under the European Union\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9cEverything But Arms\xe2\x80\x9d initiative. The top destinations for Cambodia\xe2\x80\x99s exports are the United States, Britain and Germany.\nWestern governments should use this economic leverage to urge the Hun Sen administration to respect Cambodians\xe2\x80\x99 political freedoms, setting clear conditions and red lines for further budget assistance and further preferential trade access that would require the protection of human rights.\nThe private sector also has a role to play, particularly large companies involved with Cambodia\xe2\x80\x99s garment sector. Textiles and footwear account for 80 percent of the country\xe2\x80\x99s total export revenue, and some 700,000 jobs. Major buyers like H&M, Adidas and Zara have managed to influence government policy in Cambodia in the past, including to secure a higher minimum wage and various protections for workers in the garment industry. Now they should use their clout to help protect democracy in Cambodia. After all, doing so would also help protect the stability of the country and, by the same token, their business interests.\nThe Cambodian people are hungry for political change. They \n during the general election in 2013, and again in local elections a few months ago. I see it and hear it whenever I speak to my constituents in the western province of Battambang. They ask for more jobs, fair wages, decent prices for their crops, access to health care and relief from the crushing weight of microcredit loans.\nCambodia\xe2\x80\x99s voters must be allowed to choose their leaders next year in a process that is free and fair, and credible. Mr. Kem Sokha must be freed \xe2\x80\x94 immediately and unconditionally.\n'
