aS'In the first year of his presidency, Donald Trump has achieved at least three things that few presidents ever have. His approval rating is in the 30s. His former aides \xe2\x80\x94 and reportedly the president himself \xe2\x80\x94 are under federal investigation. And members of Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s own party are running what has been \n to replace him in 2020.\nBut when I hear people talk of Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s supposedly dismal future, I think of his not-so-dismal past. I was the first national television correspondent to cover Mr. Trump full-time, so I know what can happen when people ignore the unbridled enthusiasm of his crowds.\nFor more than 500 days, I watched as Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s campaign grew from an awkward rally around a backyard pool in June 2015 to a raucous, 10,000-person convention center event in November 2016. In that same time, I also watched as Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s candidacy survived a procession of death predictions.\nLately, it seems, those predictions are back. Last month, when asked whether the president will be the Republican nominee in 2020, the Republican senator from Maine, Susan Collins, told MSNBC, \xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s too difficult to say.\xe2\x80\x9d\nEvery week there\xe2\x80\x99s a new last straw: Comey, Charlottesville, Arpaio. If all else fails, Robert Mueller, the special counsel, will surely take him down, right?\nWhen I was out on the road following Mr. Trump, I sneaked in a bit of \xe2\x80\x9cGame of Thrones\xe2\x80\x9d on my laptop between rallies. What I learned, to paraphrase the show, is that what is dead may never die \xe2\x80\x94 and, in Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s case, may only rise stronger.\nMr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s candidacy was dead when he announced it. (Mexico is sending \xe2\x80\x9crapists.\xe2\x80\x9d) His candidacy was dead when he insulted a former prisoner of war named John McCain. (\xe2\x80\x9cI like people who weren\xe2\x80\x99t captured.\xe2\x80\x9d) His candidacy was dead when he cast suspicion on an entire religion. (\xe2\x80\x9cDonald J. Trump is calling for a complete and total shutdown of Muslims entering the United States.\xe2\x80\x9d)\nDead when he attacked a federal judge, a Gold Star family, the pope. Deader than dead when he bragged about grabbing women by their genitals. (\xe2\x80\x9cWhen you\xe2\x80\x99re a star, they let you do it.\xe2\x80\x9d)\nThe more Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s candidacy was said to flatline, the more life I saw in his crowds.\nIn August 2015, a month after a high-ranking Republican National Committee operative promised me that America would never tolerate a man with no military service disparaging an American military hero, I was standing on a football field in Mobile, Ala., surrounded by 30,000 screaming Trump fans, an unheard-of turnout six months before a primary. Were they mad about the candidates words on Mr. McCain? No. The opposite. \xe2\x80\x9cHe\xe2\x80\x99s not afraid of anybody,\xe2\x80\x9d one woman told me.\nOf all the times Donald Trump was done, it is his current status as a supposedly lame duck first-term president that reminds me most of his final months on the trail. Back then, luminaries in his own party were condemning him, calling on him to drop out and researching a late-race change to the top of the ticket.\nMuch of the country was outraged. The polls were bleak. No politician had ever come back from what Mr. Trump was facing. But then, as now, the view from armchairs in Washington and newsrooms around the country missed something that it was impossible to miss out on the trail. Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s supporters were tired \xe2\x80\x94 of Washington, of the media, of waiting. And that fatigue allowed them to overlook a lot. They knew he was flawed but at least, they thought, he was on their side.\nOn one of Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s primary victory nights, in a ballroom at Mar-a-Lago, surrounded by people in diamonds and silk, I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t help wondering what Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s rally crowds would think of all the money their candidate chose to celebrate with. \xe2\x80\x9cWhy do people fighting for a raise relate to all of this?\xe2\x80\x9d I asked a man in a tuxedo. \xe2\x80\x9cBecause deep down, they know he\xe2\x80\x99s one of them,\xe2\x80\x9d he said.\n\xe2\x80\x9cTrump sees us,\xe2\x80\x9d his supporters would tell me, everywhere we stopped. \xe2\x80\x9cYou don\xe2\x80\x99t.\xe2\x80\x9d\nWhen they couldn\xe2\x80\x99t exactly cheer for him, they found ways to excuse him. Five days after the \xe2\x80\x9cAccess Hollywood\xe2\x80\x9d tape, for example, I asked an older woman in a flowery red dress what she thought of her candidate\xe2\x80\x99s theory of sexual license \xe2\x80\x94 as a lone protester was playing the tape on a loop outside a rally venue in Lakeland, Fla.\nShe smiled. \xe2\x80\x9cWhat person hasn\xe2\x80\x99t said it?\xe2\x80\x9d she said.\n\xe2\x80\x9cI haven\xe2\x80\x99t said it,\xe2\x80\x9d I said.\n\xe2\x80\x9cWell, good for you,\xe2\x80\x9d she said.\n\xe2\x80\x9cYou\xe2\x80\x99ve said you\xe2\x80\x99re going to grab women by the \xe2\x80\xa6 ?\xe2\x80\x9d I asked.\n\xe2\x80\x9cNo. Don\xe2\x80\x99t be stupid,\xe2\x80\x9d she said, and walked away.\nShortly after, Mr. Trump was onstage, kissing a pink Women for Trump sign, really pressing his face against it. The crowd roared because they thought it was funny and because it was a clear rebuke to anyone offended by what Mr. Trump waved away as \xe2\x80\x9clocker room talk.\xe2\x80\x9d\nSometimes Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s supporters had to justify or ignore his positions, too. Sure, they liked a lot of his policies and ideas, but they weren\xe2\x80\x99t married to any of them. They wanted the man above all. And if he said it, they\xe2\x80\x99d find a way to support it, even if he reversed himself the next day.\nI once asked a man heading into a rally why he supported Donald Trump.\n\xe2\x80\x9cBecause he is going to build a wall,\xe2\x80\x9d the man said.\n\xe2\x80\x9cWhat if he doesn\xe2\x80\x99t?\xe2\x80\x9d I countered.\n\xe2\x80\x9cI trust his judgment,\xe2\x80\x9d the man said.\nThey trusted his judgment and on Election Day they trusted Mr. Trump more than they trusted any of us. That\xe2\x80\x99s why when members of the media pronounced his candidacy dead, his supporters knew the opposite was true. It was never more alive.\nMaybe that has changed. I don\xe2\x80\x99t know. Nobody does. The building blocks of political life are too complex to predict, too unstable to rely on. But I do know what political devotion looks like, and I do know what happens when you choose to discount it.\n'
