aS'LONDON \xe2\x80\x94 I think David Cameron was the worst prime minister Britain has had in the 40 years I\xe2\x80\x99ve been alive, but his replacement, Theresa May, is competing hard for the title. She has jettisoned the strategic sense that was Mr. Cameron\xe2\x80\x99s only worthwhile talent, and has scrapped his best initiative: fighting international corruption and tax evasion with financial transparency.\n leaked in 2015 showed how years earlier Swiss bankers had conspired with wealthy Westerners to help them dodge taxes. Last year, the \n revealed the use of shell companies to help corrupt officials hide their money.\nThis month, journalists in a dozen countries uncovered how \n had laundered billions of dollars through companies in Britain with accounts at a Danish bank in Estonia, for the benefit of people in Germany, France, Iran, Kazakhstan, Britain and elsewhere. Similar scams have involved officials throughout the world, from \n to \n.\nThe charge sheet against Mr. Cameron is common knowledge. It was he who gave us Brexit, by \n demanded primarily by a few dozen golf-club bores in his own party. It was he who, more than anyone, \n and as soon as it failed \n for lucrative \n.\nBut as Britain finally starts considering the detailed legislation needed to remove us from the European Union, it is becoming clear that Mr. Cameron understood the reasons why so many voters across the West feel alienated from their governments, and he attempted to tackle the root causes, in a way that Ms. May does not.\nIn the decade since the financial crisis, public anger has simmered over the way rich individuals and corporations game the international financial system to avoid paying their fair share. In Britain, those ploys include the tax-minimization schemes of companies like \n and are symbolized by the corrupt officials \xe2\x80\x94 \n, \n, \n \xe2\x80\x94 who launder their stolen cash and besmirched reputations through British institutions, spending their dirty money on \n.\nHundreds of billions of pounds of illicit money pass through British banks every year, and the National Crime Agency \n money laundering \xe2\x80\x9ca strategic threat to the United Kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s economy and reputation.\xe2\x80\x9d Billions more are said to transit through Britain\xe2\x80\x99s overseas territories and dependencies \xe2\x80\x94 the Cayman and British Virgin Islands, Bermuda, Gibraltar, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man \xe2\x80\x94 all of which make a lucrative living by undercutting onshore economies.\nAll this dirty money is indeed a threat, but its concentration in Britain is also an opportunity. If Britain cleaned itself up, it would deny tax cheats, criminals, kleptocrats and \n access to one of the world\xe2\x80\x99s largest financial centers, and severely restrict their room for maneuver.\nIf democracies don\xe2\x80\x99t rein in the world\xe2\x80\x99s richest citizens and restrain the widening gap between the 0.1 percent and the rest, they will not stay democratic for long. And since today money flows seamlessly through the globalized financial system, stopping it requires international cooperation.\nThis is why the Cameron government put joint efforts against tax avoidance and corruption at the top of the agenda when it chaired \n back in 2013. Even the watered-down final declaration still looks groundbreaking. Information about company ownership should be made available to the authorities (hello, \n and the \n!). Companies should stop \n to minimize their tax bills (\n beware). Poor countries should be helped to obtain the taxes they\xe2\x80\x99re owed (from the trade in \n, say).\nThe hope was that tackling the misuse of the financial system and corruption in developing nations would help solve many of the world\xe2\x80\x99s most pressing problems: poverty, economic stagnation, illegal immigration, even terrorism. \xe2\x80\x9cCorruption adds 10 percent to business costs globally,\xe2\x80\x9d Mr. Cameron said in a speech in Singapore in July 2015, and \xe2\x80\x9ccutting corruption by just 10 percent could benefit the global economy by $380 billion every year.\xe2\x80\x9d\nEven while the referendum loomed, and Britain\xe2\x80\x99s fate teetered on the thin margins of opinion polls, Mr. Cameron maintained his focus on this global problem. In May last year, the month before the Brexit tsunami capsized his premiership, he hosted an \n in London and won \n from dozens of countries to do more to open up their economies and combat financial crime.\nBut then the Brexit referendum happened, Britain turned inward and all that stopped. The Cameron government had promised to publish its \n by the end of 2016. No strategy has yet emerged. As Jon Benton, who headed the National Crime Agency\xe2\x80\x99s International Corruption Unit and worked in the cabinet office in the months before the summit in May 2016, told me earlier this month: \xe2\x80\x9cWhen Theresa May took over, the anticorruption phone just stopped ringing.\xe2\x80\x9d\nInstead, we had the Conservative Party\xe2\x80\x99s manifesto for the entirely unnecessary election that Ms. May fluffed earlier this year. It does not mention the word \xe2\x80\x9ccorruption\xe2\x80\x9d once, and contains just a few bromides about tax avoidance. It also pledges to strip the Serious Fraud Office of its independence, which is an inexplicable response to that office\xe2\x80\x99s winning \n of the \n against corporate corruption in British history and pushing for more, largely thanks to \n introduced by Mr. Cameron\xe2\x80\x99s government.\nBrexit didn\xe2\x80\x99t just doom the prime minister\xe2\x80\x99s career, it also doomed the campaign he was leading to improve the world.\nThe irony here is that the very problems Mr. Cameron was seeking to cure helped drive the movement that dethroned him. A powerful pro-Brexit poster featured thousands of brown-skinned people queuing to enter the European Union, along with the words \xe2\x80\x9c\n.\xe2\x80\x9d Mr. Cameron\xe2\x80\x99s anticorruption campaign was supposed to help improve these immigrants\xe2\x80\x99 home countries so that they could stay put. Instead, anti-immigrant sentiment and public distrust of politicians\xe2\x80\x99 financial integrity won the day. A populist insurgency delivered Brexit, and that is now scuttling efforts to clean up Britain\xe2\x80\x99s tax havens, perhaps indefinitely.\nI never voted for David Cameron, nor did I support him while he was in office. But we shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t let his worst mistake destroy his best initiative.\n'
