aS'I was 13 when the black woman I was rooting for on \xe2\x80\x9cAmerican Idol\xe2\x80\x9d won. After black women failed to reach the top spot in the first two seasons, Fantasia finally did. With vocals straight out of a church choir in North Carolina, she deserved it.\nAll the black people I knew \xe2\x80\x94 my mom, classmates and acquaintances \xe2\x80\x94 were so proud. We celebrated this moment together. Fantasia\xe2\x80\x99s victory on one of America\xe2\x80\x99s most watched television shows at the time wasn\xe2\x80\x99t just a win for her: It was a win for \n.\nIssa Rae, a co-creator and the star of the HBO sitcom \xe2\x80\x9cInsecure,\xe2\x80\x9d stood on the Emmys\xe2\x80\x99 red carpet on Sunday and proudly proclaimed to a Variety reporter who asked which people she was cheering for, \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m rooting for everybody black.\xe2\x80\x9d When I heard that, I jumped up and shouted: \xe2\x80\x9cSame, Sis! Same!\xe2\x80\x9d Because that\xe2\x80\x99s what I\xe2\x80\x99ve been doing all my life. And apparently many other people have, too, because Variety\xe2\x80\x99s video went viral on Twitter, garnering more than 16,000 retweets and countless reshares up and down my social media timelines.\nMs. Rae told the reporter what so many black people have told their family members at dinner, their friends on group texts and their black co-workers over water cooler talk. As many obstacles as we face in our lives, there are times when we \n to see one another win.\nBut what so many people missed in her comment is that expressing black pride is not the same as being racist toward whites.\n\xe2\x80\x9cTalk about racist! You are one!\xe2\x80\x9d a Twitter user wearing a \xe2\x80\x9cMake America Great Again\xe2\x80\x9d hat wrote.\nMs. Rae\xe2\x80\x99s critics don\xe2\x80\x99t understand that when it comes to racial pride, the playing field is not level. Black pride does not carry the power to shut others out as white pride does. And that\xe2\x80\x99s the difference. Hollywood has a long history of privileging whiteness, from who gets to greenlight movie ideas to whom studios target for consumption. While white people have the luxury of turning on any given channel and seeing themselves reflected with nuance and depth onscreen, black people haven\xe2\x80\x99t been so fortunate.\nSo it\xe2\x80\x99s no surprise that Issa Rae, who is redefining how TV shows portray black millennials, gave her black colleagues props at the Emmys. In fact, it\xe2\x80\x99s the support from black viewers who religiously watched her web series \xe2\x80\x9cAwkward Black Girl\xe2\x80\x9d that helped her become the first black woman to create and star in a scripted series for HBO.\nThough \xe2\x80\x9cInsecure\xe2\x80\x9d wasn\xe2\x80\x99t nominated this year, Ms. Rae was there to unequivocally support others who broke down more of Hollywood\xe2\x80\x99s white-male-dominated doors. And it was genuine: Later that night, she \n her congratulations to Lena Waithe, who became the first black woman to win an Emmy for comedy writing.\n\xe2\x80\x9cYou\xe2\x80\x99ve been killing it for SO long! Get. Yours. Boo! @LenaWaithe #Emmys #BlacksAllZay #SaidWhatISaid,\xe2\x80\x9d she wrote, affirming her initial comment.\nMs. Waithe replied with reciprocal support: \xe2\x80\x9cLove you sis! You got next!! I have a feeling your speech gon be way funnier than mine.\xe2\x80\x9d\nWhen black artists are honored at an esteemed award show like the Emmys, it\xe2\x80\x99s no secret whom we want to win. The fact that black actors, writers and directors in 2017 are still becoming the \xe2\x80\x9cfirst\xe2\x80\x9d black person to ever receive \xe2\x80\x9cX\xe2\x80\x9d award should make that clear.\nBlack pride isn\xe2\x80\x99t designed to block the progress of others. It is meant to empower and create space for black people to celebrate and honor ourselves in a country that tells us in no uncertain terms that black lives do not matter. It\xe2\x80\x99s a necessary escape when racial tension in the world is too much to bear. It\xe2\x80\x99s a tool for survival in a world that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t want to see you win.\nWe take enormous joy in seeing Lena Waithe, Donald Glover and Sterling K. Brown walk away with trophies. Their wins give us more hope that our stories will be told in more nuanced, sensitive and multidimensional ways. We will continue to celebrate one another and will always be \xe2\x80\x9crooting for everybody black.\xe2\x80\x9d\n'
