aS" A North Korean state agency threatened on Thursday to use nuclear weapons to \xe2\x80\x9csink\xe2\x80\x9d Japan and reduce the United States to \xe2\x80\x9cashes and darkness\xe2\x80\x9d for supporting a U.N. Security Council resolution and sanctions over its latest nuclear test. \nThe Korea Asia-Pacific Peace Committee, which handles the North\xe2\x80\x99s external ties and propaganda, also called for the breakup of the Security Council, which it called \xe2\x80\x9ca tool of evil\xe2\x80\x9d made up of \xe2\x80\x9cmoney-bribed\xe2\x80\x9d countries that move at the order of the United States. \n\xe2\x80\x9cThe four islands of the archipelago should be sunken into the sea by the nuclear bomb of Juche. Japan is no longer needed to exist near us,\xe2\x80\x9d the committee said in a statement carried by the North\xe2\x80\x99s official KCNA news agency.   \nJuche is the North\xe2\x80\x99s ruling ideology that mixes Marxism and an extreme form of go-it-alone nationalism preached by state founder Kim Il Sung, the grandfather of the current leader, Kim Jong Un. \nRegional tension has risen markedly since the reclusive North conducted its sixth, and by far its most powerful, nuclear test on Sept. 3, following a series of missile tests, including one that flew over Japan. \nThe 15-member Security Council voted unanimously on a U.S.-drafted resolution and a new round of sanctions on Monday in response, banning North Korea\xe2\x80\x99s textile exports that are the second largest only to coal and mineral, and capping fuel supplies. \nThe North reacted to the latest action by the Security Council, which had the backing of veto-holding China and Russia, by reiterating threats to destroy the United States, Japan and South Korea. \n\xe2\x80\x9cLet\xe2\x80\x99s reduce the U.S. mainland into ashes and darkness. Let\xe2\x80\x99s vent our spite with mobilization of all retaliation means which have been prepared till now,\xe2\x80\x9d the statement said. \nJapan\xe2\x80\x99s Nikkei stock index and dollar/yen currency pared gains, although traders said that was more because of several Chinese economic indicators released on Thursday rather than a reaction to the North\xe2\x80\x99s latest statement. \nSouth Korea\xe2\x80\x99s won also edged down around the same time over domestic financial concerns. \nDespite the North\xe2\x80\x99s threats, South Korean President Moon Jae-in said he was against having nuclear weapons in his country, either by developing its own arsenal or bringing back U.S. tactical nuclear weapons that were withdrawn in the early 1990s. \n\xe2\x80\x9cTo respond to North Korea by having our own nuclear weapons will not maintain peace on the Korean peninsula and could lead to a nuclear arms race in northeast Asia,\xe2\x80\x9d Moon said in an interview with CNN. \nSouth Korea\xe2\x80\x99s Unification Ministry also said it planned to provide $8 million through the U.N. World Food Programme and UNICEF to help infants and pregnant women in the North. \nThe move marks Seoul\xe2\x80\x99s first humanitarian assistance for the North since its fourth nuclear test in January 2016 and is based on a longstanding policy of separating humanitarian aid from politics, the ministry said. \n\xe2\x80\x9cDANCING TO THE TUNE\xe2\x80\x9d \nThe North\xe2\x80\x99s latest threats also singled out Japan for \xe2\x80\x9cdancing to the tune\xe2\x80\x9d of the United States, saying it should never be pardoned for not offering a sincere apology for its \xe2\x80\x9cnever-to-be-condoned crimes against our people\xe2\x80\x9d, an apparent reference to Japan\xe2\x80\x99s wartime aggression. \nIt also referred to South Korea as \xe2\x80\x9ctraitors and dogs\xe2\x80\x9d of the United States. \nJapan criticized the North\xe2\x80\x99s statement harshly. \n\xe2\x80\x9cThis announcement is extremely provocative and egregious. It is something that markedly heightens regional tension and is absolutely unacceptable,\xe2\x80\x9d Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga told reporters. \nJapanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, visiting India, called for strict enforcement of the U.N. resolution, saying the world must force a change. \nThe 15-member Security Council voted unanimously on a U.S.-drafted resolution and a new round of sanctions against North Korea on Monday in response to its latest and most powerful test, banning North Korea\xe2\x80\x99s textile exports that are the second largest only to coal and mineral, and capping fuel supplies. \nNorth Korea had already rejected the Security Council resolution, vowing to press ahead with its nuclear and missile programs. \nA tougher initial U.S. draft of Monday\xe2\x80\x99s resolution was weakened to win the support of China, the North\xe2\x80\x99s lone major ally, and Russia. Significantly, it stopped short of imposing a full embargo on oil exports to North Korea, most of which come from China. \nThe latest sanctions also make it illegal for foreign firms to form commercial joint ventures with North Korean entities. \nU.S. President Donald Trump has vowed that North Korea will never be allowed to threaten the United States with a nuclear-tipped missile, but has also asked China to do more to rein in its neighbor. China in turn favors an international response to the problem. \nChinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Hua Chunying said the international community had reached a \xe2\x80\x9chigh consensus\xe2\x80\x9d on trying to realize a peaceful solution. \n\xe2\x80\x9cWe urge the relevant directly involved parties to seize the opportunity and have the political nerve to make the correct political choice as soon as possible,\xe2\x80\x9d Hua told a regular press briefing. \nThe North accuses the United States, which has 28,500 troops in South Korea, of planning to invade and regularly threatens to destroy it and its Asian allies. \nThe United States and South Korea are technically still at war with North Korea because the 1950-53 Korean conflict ended with a truce and not a peace treaty. \n(For a graphic on North Korea's missile and nuclear tests, click: \n) \n"
