aS" Russia accused the West on Thursday of \xe2\x80\x9cwhipping up hysteria\xe2\x80\x9d over large-scale military exercises currently underway in eastern Europe and denied charges that they were being conducted with a lack of transparency. \nThe exercises, codenamed \xe2\x80\x9cZapad\xe2\x80\x9d, or \xe2\x80\x9cWest\xe2\x80\x9d, started on Thursday and will last until Sept. 20. They are being conducted  on military ranges in Belarus, western Russia, Russia\xe2\x80\x99s exclave of Kaliningrad and in the Baltic Sea. \n\xe2\x80\x9cWe reject complaints of these exercises not being transparent,\xe2\x80\x9d Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov told a conference call with reporters. \xe2\x80\x9cWe believe that whipping up hysteria around these exercises is a provocation.\xe2\x80\x9d \n(For a graphic on Russia's Zapad war games click \n) \n\xe2\x80\x9cIt is a normal practice for any country to hold such exercises. Everything is being held in line with international law,\xe2\x80\x9d Peskov said. \nRussian President Vladimir Putin may visit one of the stages of these drills, he said. \nNATO is closely watching the exercises and says they are larger than the 12,700 servicemen Moscow has publicized, actually numbering some 100,000 troops, and involve firing nuclear-capable ballistic missiles. \nRussia\xe2\x80\x99s defense ministry reiterated on Thursday that the exercises, which will last until Sept. 20, are of a purely defensive nature and are not a threat to any third country or group of countries. \nBut NATO officials say the drills will simulate a conflict with the U.S.-led alliance intended to show Russia\xe2\x80\x99s ability to mass large numbers of troops at short notice in the event of a conflict. \nAmid allegations about Moscow\xe2\x80\x99s aggressive ambitions from its post-communist neighbors, Russia\xe2\x80\x99s defense ministry has said that it does not intend to use the drills as a springboard to attack Lithuania, Poland or Ukraine. \nMoscow says it is the West that threatens stability in eastern Europe, because NATO has put a 4,000-strong multinational force in the Baltics and Poland. \nRussian military analysts say the current exercises are a far cry from the \xe2\x80\x9cZapad-1981\xe2\x80\x9d war games with the Soviet Union\xe2\x80\x99s allies from the Warsaw Pact. Those involved more than 110,000 troops and their scenario included a lightning defeat of NATO forces in Europe.  \nRussia\xe2\x80\x99s defense ministry said the current drills involve some 7,200 troops from Belarus and 5,500 from Russia, up to 70 aircraft and helicopters, up to 680 units of military hardware, including 250 tanks, up to 200 artillery pieces, multiple rocket launchers and mortars, and up to 10 warships.  \n"
