aS'A year ago, when President Barack Obama \n that, given Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s progress on democracy, the United States would lift remaining sanctions on Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s military, rights groups warned that \n was premature: The country\xe2\x80\x99s democratic transition was incomplete, they said, the military retained vast powers and its record on human rights was dismal.\nIt is now tragically clear that those concerns were well founded. The Myanmar military\xe2\x80\x99s vicious crackdown against the Muslim Rohingya minority in Rakhine State has caused at least \n to flee to Bangladesh in the past few weeks alone. On Sept. 11, the United Nations human rights chief, Zeid Ra\xe2\x80\x99ad al-Hussein, accused Myanmar of carrying out \xe2\x80\x9ca textbook example of \n\xe2\x80\x9d against the Rohingya.\nMuch blame has been heaped on Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s leader, the democracy activist and Nobel Peace Prize winner Daw Aung San Suu Kyi. That is\n: Instead of condemning the military crackdown, she has complained that reports of ethnic cleansing are a \xe2\x80\x9chuge iceberg of misinformation.\xe2\x80\x9d Ms. Aung San Suu Kyi, however, has no direct control over the military. The person most responsible for the ethnic cleansing of the Rohingya \xe2\x80\x94 and who has the power to stop it \xe2\x80\x94 is \n, the commander in chief.\nOn Monday, the White House issued a\n of concern about \xe2\x80\x9cmassive displacement and victimization\xe2\x80\x9d of people in Rakhine State and called for Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s authorities to \xe2\x80\x9crespect the rule of law, stop the violence\xe2\x80\x9d and put in place the recommendations of a \n led by a former United Nations secretary general, Kofi Annan, to address the root causes of the Rohingya\xe2\x80\x99s plight, including denial of citizenship for them. On Tuesday, the European Parliament adopted a \n condemning the situation and, on Wednesday, the \n called for \xe2\x80\x9cimmediate steps to end the violence in Rakhine.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThese are welcome words, but there is no indication that General Min Aung Hlaing cares a hoot what the world thinks. The only thing that may get his attention is what forced the military to accept a measure of democracy in Myanmar: economic sanctions.\nYet with \n backing Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s military, there is little chance the Security Council will vote for new sanctions. There is nothing, however, to stop the United States from acting on its own. Senator John McCain\xe2\x80\x99s \n on Tuesday that he would seek to halt plans to expand military ties with Myanmar is a step in the right direction. The Senate could go further and move to restore sanctions against Myanmar\xe2\x80\x99s military unless the carnage stops, humanitarian aid groups are allowed back into Rakhine State, United Nations investigators are permitted to do their job there and the Rohingya are restored safely to their homes as full citizens of Myanmar.\n'
