aS'That was only one in \n on Sept. 11 by ESPN host Jemele Hill in which Hill goes on to say that Trump is \xe2\x80\x9cthe most ignorant, offensive president of my lifetime,\xe2\x80\x9d that he hired and courted white supremacists, that \xe2\x80\x9cHis rise is a direct result of white supremacy,\xe2\x80\x9d that \xe2\x80\x9cif he were not white, he never would have been elected.\xe2\x80\x9d Hill insinuates that the Republican Party \xe2\x80\x9chas done nothing but endorse/promote white supremacy.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThese tweets caused quite a stir. The White House perpetual lie-generator and press secretary, \n, said that it was a fireable offense for ESPN. Sanders\xe2\x80\x99s statement, of course, was not without its own controversy. As \n:\n\xe2\x80\x9cThe Democratic Coalition, an anti-Trump Super PAC, has filed an ethics complaint against White House Press Secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders with the Office of Government Ethics for her comments calling on ESPN host Jemele Hill to be fired.\xe2\x80\x9d\nAOL continued:\n\xe2\x80\x9cThe group claims federal law prohibits government employees from influencing \xe2\x80\x98a private entity\xe2\x80\x99s employment \xe2\x80\xa6 solely on the basis of partisan political affiliation.\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d\nThen on Friday, Trump himself weighed in, because obviously there are no more pressing matters that need his attention, oh like, say, North Korea continuing to launch missiles over Japan, for one.\nTrump tweeted:\n\xe2\x80\x9cESPN is paying a really big price for its politics (and bad programming). People are dumping it in RECORD numbers. Apologize for untruth!\xe2\x80\x9d\nThis tweet, for me, changed the conversation. It moved the discussion from propriety and in-house rules of conduct by a brand, to a question of veracity. Was what Hill said untrue, as Trump\xe2\x80\x99s tweet suggests, or is Trump in fact a white supremacist who has surrounded himself with white supremacists and whose party courted white supremacists?\nTwo of those points can be quickly put to rest. First, there is no question that Trump has hired someone who was at least a booster of white supremacists: Steve Bannon. In a sinister act of double signaling, Bannon was hired as the Trump campaign\xe2\x80\x99s chief executive on the same day that Trump started \n to black voters in Milwaukee.\nAlso, while the Republican Party clearly stands for more than white supremacy and the promotion of that intellectually fallacious concept, the party has often turned a blind eye to the racists in its midst and done far too little to extricate them.\nBut then the question remains: Is Trump himself a white supremacist?\nThis question is almost unanswerable in the absolute, but there is mounting circumstantial evidence pointing in a most disquieting direction.\nFirst, we must submit that Trump is not particularly discerning in the administration of his insults. As \n pointed out in July, \xe2\x80\x9cTrump is on track to insult 650 people, places and things on Twitter by the end of his first term.\xe2\x80\x9d He is often reflexive with his derisions, attacking those who criticize or condemn him. Many of Trump\xe2\x80\x99s lackeys laud his instinct to counterpunch. When Trump attacked MSNBC host Mika Brzezinski, \n, \xe2\x80\x9cWhen the president gets hit, he\xe2\x80\x99s going to hit back harder.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThey paint it as strength, although it is clearly weakness. It is a masking of fragility with aggression. And the traditionally marginalized \xe2\x80\x94 women, racial, religious and ethnic minorities \xe2\x80\x94 are treated to a particularly personal strain of Trump\xe2\x80\x99s venom. In Trump\xe2\x80\x99s eyes, Barack Obama wasn\xe2\x80\x99t simply a bad president, he was illegitimate and inferior, a person who couldn\xe2\x80\x99t possibly be as talented as the world thought he was. He questioned whether Obama had actually attended his prestigious colleges and insisted that Obama\xe2\x80\x99s memoir was \n for him to have written it, that it must have been written by a white man.\nIs Trump patriarchal and misogynistic? Definitely. But, what of white supremacy?\nIt is clear that Trump is hero among white supremacists: He panders to them, he is slow to condemn them and when that condemnation manifests, it is often forced and tepid. Trump never seems to be worried about offending anyone except Vladimir Putin and white supremacists.\nWhat does that say about him? How can you take comfort among and make common cause with white supremacists and not assimilate to their sensibilities?\nI say that it can\xe2\x80\x99t be done. If you are not completely opposed to white supremacy, you are quietly supporting it. If you continue to draw equivalencies between white supremacists and the people who oppose them \xe2\x80\x94 as Trump did \n last week \xe2\x80\x94 you have crossed the racial Rubicon and moved beyond quiet support to vocal support. You have made an allegiance and dug a trench in the war of racial hostilities.\nHill may have pushed into the realm of hyperbole with a few of her statements \xe2\x80\x94 it was Twitter after all \xe2\x80\x94 but I judge the spirit of her assessment to be true.\nEither Trump is himself a white supremacist or he is a fan and defender of white supremacists, and I quite honestly am unable to separate the two designations.\n'
