aS'This week President Trump \n to enshrine into law protections for young illegal immigrants brought to the United States as children. Within a matter of days, these young people went from fearing deportation to homelands some had never known, to having a potential shot at citizenship.\nDid this mark the arrival of a new, compassionate, capable Donald Trump?\nSadly, probably not. Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s actions are rarely underpinned by principles, or a vision of who we are as a nation. Even on matters of near-perfect moral clarity, he is often transactional and capricious. If he does the right thing, there must be an angle.\nHis word is never final; it\xe2\x80\x99s only the latest in a never-ending set of tactical adjustments made with one eye on his poll numbers, and the other on Fox News. If it benefits Mr. Trump personally to renege on this week\xe2\x80\x99s \n with Democrats and woo xenophobes and bigots instead of reviving the \xe2\x80\x9cDream Act,\xe2\x80\x9d he will.\nIf his core supporters thought his sympathy for Dreamers was evidence that he was getting wobbly on immigration, he made clear they could still count on his sympathy for racists. Soon after \n, the Senate\xe2\x80\x99s lone black Republican, privately scolded him for his \xe2\x80\x9csterile\xe2\x80\x9d response to \xe2\x80\x9chate groups who over three centuries of this country\xe2\x80\x99s history have made it their mission to create upheaval in minority communities,\xe2\x80\x9d Mr. Trump once again asserted what he saw as an \n who marched in Charlottesville, Va., and those who aggressively opposed them. And while he did sign a c\n denouncing these hate groups, his refusal to unequivocally reject them is what led to the unanimously approved measure to begin with.\nIt was Mr. Trump, too, who had placed those young immigrants in jeopardy of deportation last week, when he had his attorney general, Jeff Sessions, \n to President Barack Obama\xe2\x80\x99s five-year-old executive order \xe2\x80\x94 Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals \xe2\x80\x94 which let them live, work and go to school in the United States. Almost immediately after Mr. Sessions denounced these \xe2\x80\x9cDreamers\xe2\x80\x9d as job-stealers and potential gang members, Mr. Trump seemed to shift, amid a wave of outrage at the administration\xe2\x80\x99s cruelty.\nOn Wednesday night, Mr. Trump had dinner with Chuck Schumer and Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic leaders of the Senate and House, who later \n that the president had agreed to their proposal \xe2\x80\x9cto enshrine the protections of DACA into law quickly,\xe2\x80\x9d along with border security measures, but no border wall.\nWhat followed the next day was the now familiar ping-ponging of tweets and contradictory assertions from Mr. Trump and others that threw Congress into chaos, as Republicans tried to parse what the president meant. There would be a path to citizenship, or there would be no such path? The wall was being built, or the wall would be built later?\nConservatives erupted. Ann Coulter, author of \xe2\x80\x9cIn Trump We Trust,\xe2\x80\x9d unleashed a stream of protests, demanding that he be impeached.\nOf course, Mr. Trump always saw the wall as more of a campaign slogan than a possibility. Even congressional Republicans are balking at handing him billions for a quixotic project that won\xe2\x80\x99t be completed for years, if ever.\nAmid Thursday\xe2\x80\x99s uproar, the conservative Never-Trump stalwart William Kristol had sound advice on dealing with Mr. Trump.\n\xe2\x80\x9cTo liberals, centrists & conservatives,\xe2\x80\x9d he \n, \xe2\x80\x9cwork for good policies during Trump\xe2\x80\x99s presidency; never lose sight of his unfitness to be president.\xe2\x80\x9d\nNo one should cheer Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s latest moves as a pivot toward principles. So far, his main operating principle seems to be service to himself.\n'
