aS'On Wednesday, Harvard\xe2\x80\x99s Kennedy School announced that Chelsea Manning, the former Army intelligence analyst and whistle-blower, would be a visiting fellow this fall. The reaction was swift: A day later, Michael Morell, a former acting director of the C.I.A. and also a visiting fellow at the school, resigned from his own fellowship in protest. His resignation was quickly followed by the current director of the C.I.A., Mike Pompeo, canceling a speech scheduled at the school. In a statement, Mr. Pompeo unilaterally declared Ms. Manning a \xe2\x80\x9ctraitor.\xe2\x80\x9d\nOn Friday morning, the school folded, disinviting Ms. Manning in a cowardly act that does immense disservice to its students and the public debate around government secrecy.\nIt\xe2\x80\x99s remarkable that one of the country\xe2\x80\x99s premier educational institutions would bow to C.I.A. pressure and reject a person who has arguably done more to contribute to the public\xe2\x80\x99s understanding of world diplomacy than anyone else in modern times. In early 2010, Ms. Manning leaked a trove of hundreds of thousands of State Department and Defense Department documents, an archive that opened an unparalleled window into American foreign policy. Its documents have been referenced by major news organizations \n that it\xe2\x80\x99s impossible to count them.\nThe important revelations in the Manning documents \xe2\x80\x94 originally leaked to WikiLeaks and published in conjunction with The New York Times and other newspapers \xe2\x80\x94 are also too numerous to name, but they include the fact that the United States \n in Iraq than the government had admitted publicly, that United States soldiers \n and that the United States \n by American soldiers.\nMs. Manning was convicted of violating the Espionage Act and other offenses in 2013, and was sentenced to 35 years in prison. (My organization helped raise money for her legal defense.) In January, President Barack Obama, in one of his last acts in office, commuted her sentence. Altogether, she spent seven years in prison \xe2\x80\x94 more time behind bars than any other leaker in American history. She was also subject to deplorable treatment while in custody that the \n at the time constituted cruel, inhuman and degrading treatment and that more than 250 law professors \n. Whatever your opinion on the value of her disclosures, it should be clear to everyone that Ms. Manning was unduly punished for her supposed crime, and she deserves the opportunity to re-enter the public debate without worrying about the C.I.A. bullying private institutions to disavow her at every turn.\nMr. Morrell, in his resignation letter, quoted unnamed officials claiming Ms. Manning \xe2\x80\x9cput the lives of U.S. soldiers at risk,\xe2\x80\x9d without citing any specific examples. This is a common charge against her, and an unfounded one: The evidence of \xe2\x80\x9cdamage\xe2\x80\x9d from Ms. Manning\xe2\x80\x99s leaks has been grossly exaggerated from the start. During her trial, the government could not point to anyone, soldier or otherwise, who was physically harmed by WikiLeaks\xe2\x80\x99 publications. Even at the time of the leaks, State Department officials were privately admitting that \n the harm the leaks caused to bolster their case.\nHarvard\xe2\x80\x99s decision to rescind Ms. Manning\xe2\x80\x99s invitation is about more than academic spinelessness. In \n defending the decision, Douglas W. Elmendorf, the dean of the Kennedy School, said, \xe2\x80\x9cI think we should weigh, for each potential visitor, what members of the Kennedy School community could learn from that person\xe2\x80\x99s visit against the extent to which that person\xe2\x80\x99s conduct fulfills the values of public service to which we aspire.\xe2\x80\x9d\nIf that\xe2\x80\x99s the Kennedy School\xe2\x80\x99s new policy, let\xe2\x80\x99s take a look. Mr. Morell, for example, \n that the C.I.A. engaged in torture, even in the face of the Senate\xe2\x80\x99s damning torture report released in 2014. When asked about the agency\xe2\x80\x99s decision to conduct forced \xe2\x80\x9crectal feeding\xe2\x80\x9d on a detainee, he refused to answer whether that amounted to torture. Mr. Morell \n for indiscriminate C.I.A. drone strikes that have killed at least hundreds of civilians. He most \n when he told Charlie Rose the United States should be \xe2\x80\x9ckilling Russians and Iranians\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x94 two countries the United States is not at war with \xe2\x80\x94 in Syria.\nOther 2017 visiting fellows include Sean Spicer, President Trump\xe2\x80\x99s first press secretary, who was \n to the public on almost a daily basis by reporters, and the former Trump campaign manager Corey Lewandowski, who \n against a journalist during the 2016 campaign.\nWhat Mr. Elmendorf and the Kennedy School are saying, essentially, is that no issue or action is off topic for visiting fellows except, apparently, giving information to journalists and informing the public about what its government is doing behind closed doors.\nExcessive government secrecy, the worship of \xe2\x80\x9cnational security\xe2\x80\x9d above all else and the C.I.A.\xe2\x80\x99s disrupting presence overseas are exactly the sorts of issues that the Kennedy School should be questioning and challenging, given the myriad C.I.A. and Pentagon scandals and our country\xe2\x80\x99s constant state of war since Sept. 11. Chelsea Manning\xe2\x80\x99s act of whistle-blowing was a powerful, influential and important contribution to that debate.\n'
