aS'Kara Walker has had enough.\nSince her 1994 New York debut, at just 24 years old, at the Drawing Center, she and her artworks have been hailed as \xe2\x80\x9c\n\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9c\n\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9c\n\xe2\x80\x9d and \xe2\x80\x9c\n.\xe2\x80\x9d She has won a MacArthur fellowship, was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Letters and has been widely praised as among the most important black artists working today. No pressure or anything.\nMs. Walker is, as she writes in the artist statement for her new show at \n in New York, \xe2\x80\x9ctired of \xe2\x80\x98having a voice\xe2\x80\x99 or worse, \xe2\x80\x98being a role model.\xe2\x80\x99 \xe2\x80\x9d She is fed up with \xe2\x80\x9cbeing a featured member of my racial group and/or gender niche.\xe2\x80\x9d She also notes that her new work is not \xe2\x80\x9cactivist\xe2\x80\x9d and we shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t expect answers from her: \xe2\x80\x9cI roll my eyes, fold my arms and wait.\xe2\x80\x9d\nWell, this is what Ms. Walker rolling her eyes and folding her arms looks like: a 151-by-191-inch work at the show, in sumi ink and collage, titled \xe2\x80\x9cChrist\xe2\x80\x99s Entry Into Journalism,\xe2\x80\x9d which combines the imagined and the real as well as the past and present. My eye immediately went to the faces of James Brown and the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Then I noticed Frederick Douglass giving a Black Power salute while holding the swastika-stamped head of what appears to be Donald Trump \xe2\x80\x94 an obvious allusion to the moment, a few months back, when the president seemed to believe Douglass, who died in 1895, was alive.\nElsewhere in the illustration, the president\xe2\x80\x99s look-alike makes another appearance. This time he peeks out from between a Klansman\xe2\x80\x99s legs. The Trump-like character wags his tongue while defecating. In another part of the collage, two black girls swing on a trapeze. Look closer and you see the body of a lynched black man hanging on the branch between them.\nA white woman carries Trayvon Martin\xe2\x80\x99s hoodie-covered head on a tray. A black man is attacked by a police officer in riot gear who holds a turkey leg in one hand and a cellphone in the other. There is a Confederate battle flag. An American flag. And an arm in a Nazi salute.\nThis is just one of her pieces in a show of 22.\nWhile Ms. Walker\xe2\x80\x99s work has always reflected the realities of black America, it has typically focused on the past, particularly the slavery of African-Americans. Never has she so blatantly illustrated the modern.\nThat is why the dissonance between her canvases and her statement has rubbed many people the wrong way. One person said the statement wasn\xe2\x80\x99t \xe2\x80\x9cincredibly innovative or interesting or even resistant.\xe2\x80\x9d Another called it \xe2\x80\x9cfoolish.\xe2\x80\x9d Nell Painter, an acclaimed historian-turned-painter, \n a paradox in being \xe2\x80\x9ctired of being a role model, but still making art about slavery.\xe2\x80\x9d One critic even suggested that if Ms. Walker is sick of her platform, she should \xe2\x80\x9c\nThe outrage is tediously predictable \xe2\x80\x94 and of a piece with the debate that has flared over the political responsibility of artists and celebrities since the election of Donald Trump. Richard Prince \n an image he created of Ivanka Trump years ago and returned the money he got from selling it. In January, the artist Christo \n a project he\xe2\x80\x99d worked on for over 20 years because it was on federal land and he couldn\xe2\x80\x99t condone working to the benefit of the current government. Meryl Streep was greeted with hosannas for her outspoken criticism of the president; Taylor Swift\xe2\x80\x99s silence has been condemned.\nMs. Walker gets all this \xe2\x80\x94 perhaps better than most, given that her work has long been criticized by prominent artists, black and white, who say it is reductive. In 1997, the black artist Betye Saar \n a letter-writing campaign against Ms. Walker\xe2\x80\x99s work, the same year that Howardena Pindell, another black artist, said that Ms. Walker \xe2\x80\x9cconsciously or unconsciously seems to be catering to the bestial fantasies about blacks created by white supremacy and racism.\xe2\x80\x9d Two years later, Ms. Saar said that Ms. Walker\xe2\x80\x99s art was \xe2\x80\x9crevolting and negative and a form of betrayal to the slaves, particularly women and children\xe2\x80\x9d and that \xe2\x80\x9cit was basically for the amusement and the investment of the white art establishment.\xe2\x80\x9d As Ms. Walker wryly put it in an \n with New York magazine in April: \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re in too much of a celebrity culture, but at least that means I can be a disappointment to others.\xe2\x80\x9d\nHer finger-wagging critics are missing the point when they go after her artist statement, which is nothing less than a big middle finger to our current culture of flame wars and empty words. Her statement is another way of saying: Ignore the hot air. Open your eyes and look at the work. The work is saying something strong and clear. It said to this viewer that this country is sick and perhaps we congratulated ourselves too much and too early for moving forward. Progress can so quickly crumble into chaos.\nIf you do open your eyes, you will be schooled by a modern master on American history, racism, aesthetics and politics. It\xe2\x80\x99s far more powerful than any artist statement.\n'
