aS'Public servants are supposed to serve the public, not themselves. What part of that equation does Steven Mnuchin not understand?\nThe Trump administration\xe2\x80\x99s Treasury secretary is in hot water again. On Wednesday, ABC News \n that the Treasury Department\xe2\x80\x99s inspector general\xe2\x80\x99s office was looking at his request that a government jet fly him and his new wife on their European honeymoon. The jet costs taxpayers roughly $25,000 an hour to operate. Mr. Mnuchin, a former Goldman Sachs banker, is worth more than $300 million.\nA Treasury spokesman said Mr. Mnuchin made the request, later withdrawn, because he needed the jet\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9csecure communications.\xe2\x80\x9d Since Mr. Mnuchin is fifth in line of succession should anything happen to the president, this excuse was at least a tad more credible than the one offered for a ride he took with his wife, Louise Linton, last month that is also under official review. That trip was to Kentucky, where the couple could view the solar eclipse in the path of totality. The justification then was that Mr. Mnuchin wanted to speak with Kentuckians about tax reform and he needed to check on the gold at Fort Knox, which is presumably as safe and sound after Mr. Mnuchin\xe2\x80\x99s inspection as it was when he got there.\nTaxpayers, who are being reimbursed for Ms. Linton\xe2\x80\x99s travel, may never have known about that junket had she not decided to use a photo of herself alighting from the plane to show off her Hermes, Valentino and Tom Ford ensemble on Instagram. She then savaged a woman from Oregon who dared call the move \xe2\x80\x9c#deplorable.\xe2\x80\x9d As the clothes designers began distancing themselves, Ms. Linton apologized to America \xe2\x80\x94 in an interview with a Washington society magazine that ran a photo of her, in a ball gown, on the cover.\nMr. Mnuchin comes from a world where rich people get free stuff all the time. Now he is in a different world, one where taxpayers are on the hook. \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re starting to see a pattern with Steve Mnuchin,\xe2\x80\x9d says Walter Shaub, former chief of the Office of Government Ethics, now at the Campaign Legal Center. \xe2\x80\x9cThis is the tone from the top, that President Trump himself has set: Ethics doesn\xe2\x80\x99t matter, and high positions of public trust come with perks.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThe Mnuchins, along with \n, have lost no time establishing themselves as one of the most rapacious It couples in Washington. The \xe2\x80\x9cMoochin\xe2\x80\x99 Mnuchins\xe2\x80\x9d were a hot topic on social media on Thursday, as commenters reviewed the pair\xe2\x80\x99s outrages, the latest dubbed the \xe2\x80\x9cLove Jet.\xe2\x80\x9d Mr. Mnuchin was among the first administration grifters to draw attention from government ethics officials when he \n $95 million in assets, including houses in the Hamptons and Los Angeles and a New York City co-op, on his financial disclosure form.\nAn innocent oversight, he said. Then, \n, he, first, acknowledged that as a cabinet member he couldn\xe2\x80\x99t \xe2\x80\x9cpromote anything that I\xe2\x80\x99m involved in\xe2\x80\x9d; then, second, added, \xe2\x80\x9cbut you should all send your kids to \xe2\x80\x98Lego Batman,\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d a movie he produced. He then found himself apologizing again, sort of, in a memo to the ethics office, saying, \xe2\x80\x9cIt was not my intention to make a product endorsement.\xe2\x80\x9d\nMs. Linton, who grew up in a Scottish castle, used her gap-year stint as an aid worker in Africa as fodder for a book in which she called herself a \xe2\x80\x9cskinny white Muzungu with long angel hair,\xe2\x80\x9d writing, \xe2\x80\x9cI try to remember a smiling gaptoothed child with H.I.V. whose greatest joy was to sit on my lap and drink from a bottle of Coca-Cola.\xe2\x80\x9d\nBut hey, it\xe2\x80\x99s not like it\xe2\x80\x99s all play and no work for Mr. Mnuchin. He\xe2\x80\x99s been spending plenty of time on Capitol Hill, \n, mostly with himself, on a tax reform proposal about which very little is known except that it will probably include tax cuts for wealthy people like him. Last week, he tried to sell to skeptical conservatives Mr. Trump\xe2\x80\x99s Chuck-and-Nancy deal \xe2\x80\x94 the one with the Democratic leaders of the Senate and House to raise the debt ceiling. He was dismissed as a politically clueless former Democratic donor.\nThis Treasury secretary\xe2\x80\x99s ethical problems make Tim Geithner\xe2\x80\x99s \n look quaint. Steven Mnuchin might be a darling on Wall Street; so far, he\xe2\x80\x99s a disgrace as a public servant.\n'
