aS' U.S. President Donald Trump criticized the United Nations for bloated bureaucracy and mismanagement on his first visit on Monday to U.N. headquarters, calling for \xe2\x80\x9ctruly bold reforms\xe2\x80\x9d so it could be a greater force for world peace. \nAhead of his maiden speech to the annual U.N. General Assembly on Tuesday, Trump hosted a short event to boost support for changes to the United Nations. \n\xe2\x80\x9cIn recent years the United Nations has not reached its full potential because of bureaucracy and mismanagement, while the United Nations on a regular budget has increased by 140 percent and its staff has more than doubled since 2000,\xe2\x80\x9d Trump said. \n\xe2\x80\x9cThe United Nations must hold every level of management accountable, protect whistleblowers and focus on results rather than on process,\xe2\x80\x9d Trump said.  \n\xe2\x80\x9cI am confident that if we work together and champion truly bold reforms the United Nations will emerge as a stronger, more effective, more just and greater force for peace and harmony in the world,\xe2\x80\x9d Trump said in his first remarks at the U.N. in New York since his inauguration as president in January. \nIn a building where long statements are commonplace, Trump spoke for just four minutes. More than 120 countries were invited to attend Monday\xe2\x80\x99s reform meeting after signing on to a U.S.-drafted 10-point political declaration backing efforts by U.N. Secretary-General Antonio Guterres \xe2\x80\x9cto initiate effective, meaningful reform.\xe2\x80\x9d \nBusinessman Trump, who complained during his 2016 election campaign about the United States paying a disproportionate amount of money to the United Nations, made the point again on Monday. \n\xe2\x80\x9cWe must ensure that no one and no member state shoulders a disproportionate share of the burden and that\xe2\x80\x99s militarily or financially.\xe2\x80\x9d  \nThe United States is the biggest U.N. contributor, providing 22 percent of its $5.4 billion biennial core budget and 28.5 percent of its $7.3 billion peacekeeping budget. The contributions are agreed on by the 193-member General Assembly. \nGuterres, who also took office in January, told the meeting: \xe2\x80\x9cTo serve the people we support and the people who support us, we must be nimble and effective, flexible and efficient.\xe2\x80\x9d \nHe agreed that U.N bureaucracy was a problem that kept him up at night.     \n\xe2\x80\x9cOur shared objective is a 21st century U.N. focused more on people and less on process,\xe2\x80\x9d Guterres said. \xe2\x80\x9cValue for money while advancing shared values \xe2\x80\x93 that is our common goal.\xe2\x80\x9d \nTrump also said that all peacekeeping missions should \xe2\x80\x9chave clearly defined goals and metrics for evaluating success.\xe2\x80\x9d \nThe United States is reviewing each of the U.N. peacekeeping missions as annual mandates come up for Security Council renewal in a bid to cut costs. The United States is a veto-wielding council member, along with Britain, France, Russia and China. \nOn Sunday night, U.S. Secretary of State Rex Tillerson met with U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees Filippo Grandi.  \nWhen asked if the U.N. refugee agency could perform its current missions if the United States cut its voluntary contributions to the budget, according to a pool report Grandi answered: \xe2\x80\x9cI would say no.\xe2\x80\x9d \n\xe2\x80\x9cU.S. aid is vital to what we do to support refugees around the world and to find solutions to their situations,\xe2\x80\x9d Grandi said.  \n'
