aS'In August 1965, a resolute President Lyndon Johnson said: \xe2\x80\x9cAmerica wins the wars that she undertakes. Make no mistake about it.\xe2\x80\x9d But the strategy on which he committed America to its ill-fated intervention in Vietnam that year did not aim at winning, but at not losing. McGeorge Bundy, Johnson\xe2\x80\x99s national security adviser, later admitted as much to a biographer, saying that he had personally approved a strategy that used just enough military pressure to achieve a battlefield stalemate, which \xe2\x80\x9cwould eventually compel the Vietnamese Communists to compromise their objectives,\xe2\x80\x9d forcing them to the negotiating table or to a Korea-style armistice.\nBundy added that his strategy rested, in hindsight, on \xe2\x80\x9clittle more than an unexamined assumption.\xe2\x80\x9d The same might be said of President Trump\xe2\x80\x99s newest policy on Afghanistan. Secretary of State Rex Tillerson said that the strategy, which commits a few thousand more troops, was \xe2\x80\x9cintended to put pressure on the Taliban.\xe2\x80\x9d The idea, he said, was \xe2\x80\x9cto have the Taliban understand, you will not win a battlefield victory \xe2\x80\x94 we may not win one, but neither will you \xe2\x80\x94 so at some point, we have to come to the negotiating table and find a way to bring this to an end.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThere are two great lessons of Vietnam that the Trump administration might bear in mind before attempting to reprise the stalemate strategy that so conspicuously failed in the earlier conflict.\nThe first was formulated by a rueful Bundy, many years after the end of the Vietnam War: \xe2\x80\x9cWe ought not to ever be in a position where we are deciding, or undertaking to decide, or even trying to influence the internal power structure\xe2\x80\x9d of another country, he told his biographer, Gordon M. Goldstein. George Kennan, the historian and former diplomat, came to the same conclusion long before Bundy. In the Fulbright hearings on Vietnam in February 1966, he stated, \xe2\x80\x9cOur country should not be asked, and should not ask of itself, to shoulder the main burden of determining the political realities in any other country.\xe2\x80\x9d\nDid President Trump learn that lesson? In his Aug. 21 speech announcing the policy, he said: \xe2\x80\x9cWe are a partner and a friend, but we will not dictate to the Afghan people how to live or how to govern their own complex society. We are not nation-building again. We are killing terrorists.\xe2\x80\x9d But actions matter more than words, and a strategy based on an indefinite stalemate requires precisely what Mr. Trump says he rejects: propping up an Afghan government that cannot survive unaided for a prolonged period of time.\nAnd in fact, nation-building is exactly what America is doing in Afghanistan, as the foreign policy expert \n to the country. Only instead of \xe2\x80\x9cnation-building,\xe2\x80\x9d he heard commanders use terms like \xe2\x80\x9ccapacity-building,\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cenabling\xe2\x80\x9d and \xe2\x80\x9cworking by, through and with.\xe2\x80\x9d One could hark back to the hopeful reports of democracy-building in Vietnam in 1967, as President Nguyen Van Thieu began consolidating his military-based rule with a flawed election, carried out mainly at the insistence of the United States.\nThis brings us to the second lesson of Vietnam, articulated by Henry Kissinger at the end of 1968 in a famous Foreign Affairs essay: A denial strategy cannot in itself produce victory, especially in a conflict involving insurgents. \xe2\x80\x9cWe fought a military war; our opponents fought a political one,\xe2\x80\x9d he wrote. \xe2\x80\x9cWe sought physical attrition; our opponents aimed for our psychological exhaustion. In the process we lost sight of one of the cardinal maxims of guerrilla war: The guerrilla wins if he does not lose. The conventional army loses if it does not win.\xe2\x80\x9d\nMany years later, Mr. Kissinger, who became Richard Nixon\xe2\x80\x99s national security adviser, connected this conclusion with an additional point: America\xe2\x80\x99s inability to \xe2\x80\x9cwin\xe2\x80\x9d in Vietnam by producing a decisive outcome rendered the stalemate strategy of \xe2\x80\x9cnot losing\xe2\x80\x9d ineffective. He no doubt took pleasure in ascribing the fallacy to his rival and predecessor, Bundy.\n\xe2\x80\x9cStalemate violates the maxim that the guerrilla wins if he does not lose,\xe2\x80\x9d Mr. Kissinger told Newsweek in 2008. \xe2\x80\x9cHanoi\xe2\x80\x99s leaders had fought a decade against France and battled the United States for a similar length of time, not to achieve a political compromise, but to prevail.\xe2\x80\x9d In other words, a stalemate strategy against an ideologically motivated, insurgent-driven enemy is doomed to fail.\nThere\xe2\x80\x99s a corollary: Stalemate strategies that don\xe2\x80\x99t show rapid progress will soon eat away at public and domestic political support. Indeed, by 1967 the news media and a growing number of politicians were debating whether or not the Vietnam War was stalemated \xe2\x80\x94 overlooking, or disregarding, the fact that this was precisely the Johnson administration\xe2\x80\x99s goal. Nor was it simply a matter of bad communication: Stalemate might have made sense to Bundy, but no one in the White House or Pentagon thought it made for good P.R. And so even as the White House and the Pentagon pursued a stalemate strategy in Vietnam, at home they insisted that progress toward a conventional victory was close at hand.\nGen. William Westmoreland, who oversaw the American war effort from Saigon, was brought back to Washington twice in 1967 to reassure Congress and the American people. But his promotional efforts served only to amplify the shock of the Tet offensive in early 1968, which led Walter Cronkite, after a visit to Vietnam during the fighting, to announce, \xe2\x80\x9cTo say that we are mired in stalemate seems the only realistic, if unsatisfactory conclusion.\xe2\x80\x9d\nThis same disconnect in strategy, rhetoric and reality confronts us today. If stalemate and nation-building are the goals in Afghanistan, but the American public is led to expect a victory, then it is only a matter of time before the entire edifice collapses. And when it does, we might face the same conclusion that Cronkite drew after touring Vietnam: \xe2\x80\x9cIt is increasingly clear to this reporter that the only rational way out then will be to negotiate, not as victors, but as an honorable people who lived up to their pledge to defend democracy, and did the best they could.\xe2\x80\x9d\n'
